<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Medicines Covered by Canadian Health Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- British Columbia will become Canada
's first province to regulate Chinese medicine, according to a
report reaching here Tuesday from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
The decision to regulate Chinese health therapies came on
Monday after a three-month consultation. The province's Premier
Glen Clark suggested they be covered by the local health-care plan.
</P>
<P>
The procedures to be regulated also include energy control
therapy and manipulative therapy offered by more than 700
practitioners in British Columbia, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Currently, patients must pay the full cost for such procedures,
the report said, adding that the coverage would likely add
millions of dollars to the costs of the provincial health-care
plan.
</P>
<P>
Clark suggested, however, the public would eventually support
the idea because traditional Chinese medicines can help fight
serious illnesses when used along with western forms of medicine.
</P>
<P>
"I think at the end of the day, the more emphasis we can put on
wellness and this kind of medicine, the more money we save in our
acute care sickness model," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
