<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Plant to Become World's No.1 Tennis Ball Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has been chosen to be the
production base for sport balls of the U.S.-based sporting goods
giant Wilson company, Thai Deputy Industry Minister Suriya
Chuengrungruengkit said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Suriya said that the Universal Sportware Co. of Taiwan, the
licensed producer of Wilson sport balls, has decided to implement
its new 400-million-baht (10.8 million U.S. dollar) production
capacity expansion plan at Sampran plant in the central province
of Nakhorn Prathom.
</P>
<P>
The Thai plant will produce 60 million tennis balls annually
for sale worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The move followed the plan to close Wilson's U.S. factory,
turning the company's Thai plant into the largest one in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The expansion project, which will start production later this
year, would use 4,000 tons of natural rubber products annually,
which is expected to shore up rubber prices and help improve the
economic conditions of local plantations, the deputy minister
said.
</P>
<P>
It will also create 600 jobs in the Nakhorn Prathom province,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Universal originally planned to use China as the expanded
production base for Wilson balls, but finally decided to choose
Thailand when taking availability and quality of raw material into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Wilson now controls 20 percent of the world's market for tennis
balls. The company will also relocate its U.S. football factory to
Thailand, which has local petrochemical production to provide the
necessary raw materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
