<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Up, Trade Surplus Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports began to rise
in April while trade surplus dropped sharply in the first four
months of this year, said a Government House press release, which
was available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased 4.7 percent in terms of U.S. dollar to 4.54
billion dollars, which was considered "a positive sign of export
recovery", the press release quoted government economic ministers
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The increase includes agro-industry products and industrial
products which rose 16.3 percent and 8.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, agricultural goods, such as rice and frozen shrimp,
fell both in terms of volume and value.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of 1999, Thai exports totaled 17.6
billion dollars, or a 1.9 percent drop compared to the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
According to economic ministers, the fall of exports should be
attributed to the slowdown in demand from markets in the
Association of Southeast Asian countries, the United States and
European Union members.
</P>
<P>
Other factors leading to the export fall are high competition
from rivals like Chinese, Malaysian, Indonesian and Philippine
producers and exporters, especially those small and medium-sized
ones.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's imports recorded a 5.1 percent to 15.1
billion dollars from January to April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
