<HEADLINE> Thai WTO Chief Candidate to Attend APEC Meeting in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister
and Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, who is running for
the top post of the World Trade Organization (WTO), will go to New
Zealand to attend an APEC meeting there, a Thai Foreign Ministry
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Supachai has no plans to meet his bitter rival for the
WTO director-general post, New Zealand's former prime minister
Mike Moore, said Kobsak Chutikul, director general of the Thai
foreign Ministry's Economic Department.
</P>
<P>
Supachai is to head a Thai delegation to attend a three-day
session involving ministers of the 21-member Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum to prepare for the September summit.
</P>
<P>
The battle for the WTO's new director general has lasted for
eight months.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the WTO's 134 members postponed once again efforts
to build a consensus around either Supachai or Moore, the last two
candidates remaining in the race, until July.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak warned earlier that ill feeling stirred up by the row
over the race could cast a shadow over the APEC summit in
September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, New Zealand Ambassador to Thailand Adrian Macey said
his government had no intention of linking WTO affairs with APEC.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the New Zealand government will not invite
Moore, a member of the opposition, to the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
