<HEADLINE> Japan to Import 15,000 Rice From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has won bids to export
more than 15,000 tons of rice to Japan this year, Pracha
Charutrakulchai, director general of the Commerce Ministry's
Foreign Trade Department, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government had arranged two biddings for foreign
rice purchase this year as obliged by free trade accords of the
World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Thai suppliers won a share of 868 tons of rice from the total
25,000 tons arranged for the first bidding and won the whole lot
of 15,000 tons in the second bidding, Pracha said.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo has set an import quota of 646,300 tons of rice in this
fiscal year, which started in April, and had allowed for the first
time extra imports of rice beyond the set quota, with import
tariff of 351.17 yen (2.9 U.S. dollars) a kilogram, which would be
reduced to 341 yen (2.8 dollars) a kilo in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, with steady increase of rice exports to the Japanese
market over the past years, expected to ship at least 160,000 tons
of rice to Tokyo this year, Pracha said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
