<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sets Up Climate Information Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Asia's first climate change
information center (CCIC) was set up in the Philippines on
Tuesday, a news release of the Philippine Presidential Palace
said.
</P>
<P>
During the launching ceremony in the Presidential Palace,
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said the establishment of the
CCIC "can encourage awareness among our people regarding the
measures we can adopt to mitigate prospective adverse effects of
climate change."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Environment and Natural Resources Secretary Antonio
Cerilles said that the CCIC will disseminate information on global
warming, its impact on the Philippines, climate-friendly
technologies, and measures to mitigate and adapt to climate
change.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, Cerilles said that the CCIC will have a
collection of books on climate change, atmospheric science and
pollution, as well as compact discs and various multi-media and
video tapes concerning climate change.
</P>
<P>
He added that the center will also conceptualize and conduct
seminars and workshops on climate change to ensure that needed
information are given out and discussed by concerned groups.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Observatory under the Ateneo de Manila University
will host and operate the CCIC, while the Foundation for the
Philippine Environment will help in information dissemination and
training, Cerilles said.
</P>
<P>
Global warming has been tagged as the primary cause of extreme
weather disorders like typhoons, the El Nino and La Nina phenomena
that have brought about damages to the whole world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
