<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Contributes Much to China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's private sector has
contributed a great deal to exports, tax revenue, charity and
providing job opportunities in the past year, said an official
from the National Self-Employed Laborers Association here today.
</P>
<P>
The private sector paid over 70 billion yuan in taxes last year,
up 16.77 billion yuan compared with 1997 -- an increase of nearly
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that in 1998 the private sector
donated over one billion yuan to support charitable causes, up 385
million yuan over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The private sector also made over three million job positions
available for laid-off people in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, among the more than 17.3 million workers in
the private sector, nearly ten million were living in urban areas,
and 7.3 million were living in rural areas, up 2.2 million and 1.3
million, respectively, compared with 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Forestry "Icon" Taken Over by U.S. Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Canadian forestry "icon" MacMillan
Bloedel is being taken over by U.S. giant Weyerhaeuser Co. in an
all-stock transaction of 3.6 billion Canadian dollars (about 2.45
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The proposed merger between the second largest company in the
Canadian province of British Columbia and its U.S. rival based in
Federal Way, Washington, would create the world's largest softwood
lumber producer, "The latest example of globalization sweeping
Canada," local media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales of the new company were estimated at 19.5 billion
U.S. dollars with a stock-market value of 24.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Weyerhaeuser's friendly take over offer," which was announced
Monday, valued MacBlo's stock at a 35 percent premium over its pre-
takeover market price of 21.05 Canadian dollars (about 14.31 U.S.
dollars) a share, reports said, adding that MacBlo's directors
gave unanimous support to the deal.
</P>
<P>
Speculations about the new company, which will have one-third
of its operations in Canada, drove MacBlo stock at the Toronto
stock market Monday up by 5.15 Canadian dollars (about 3.5 U.S.
dollars) to close at 26.20 Canadian dollars (about 17.82 U.S.
dollars), a new 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
Weyerhaeuser stocks were reported down 2.63 U.S. dollars to 67.
13 dollars on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Canadian regulators and government officials need up to five
months for a sweeping review of Weyerhaeuser Co.'s planned multi-
billion dollar takeover of MacMillan Bloedel Ltd, before they
allow the blockbuster marriage to proceed.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for half of British Columbia's exports, MacMillan
Bloedel was formed by a merger of three companies in 1959. It was
first established 80 years ago by H.R. MacMillan, a native of
Newmarket, Ontario, and a cousin of novelist Mazo de la Roche.
</P>
<P>
The company employs 9,500 workers in British Columbia, down
from a peak of more than 25,000 during the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
