<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Warns Famine in Horn of Africa Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although late April brought good rains to Somalia, Ethiopia and
Kenya, an extended dry spell with only scattered rains during May
and June is likely to cut crops and livestock production, further
weakening the region' s already precarious food situation.
</P>
<P>
In Somalia, 80 percent of the country's harvest is dependent on
rains which fall between April and June. This year, it rains for
only half the normal period.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, the failure of the rains from February to May have
caused huge crop losses in areas which are already suffering from
food shortages.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, scarce rainfall and the plague of army worms will
have an adverse impact on the country's next harvest.
</P>
<P>
"We are acting now to prevent a potentially major humanitarian
crisis", said Judith Lewis, WFP country representative for
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
WFP has already approved a 40.5 million U.S. dollars emergency
 operation to feed nearly 1.2 million people desperately in need
of food in eight drought-stricken regions of Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
