<HEADLINE> Malaysia Welcomes G7 Plan to Halt Financial Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Approached by reporters on the Group of Seven (G7) and Russia's
approval Monday of a plan to halt financial speculation, Mahathir
said that Malaysia is now glad that rich nations have finally
subscribed to her conviction that financial speculation is to
blame for the current global economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He said they were now accepting Malaysia's proposal to
regulate financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The G7 approved the plan at their meeting in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, however, said that "between accepting and doing
something [about it], there is a wide gap."
</P>
<P>
He also commented on another G7 decision to provide debt
relief amounting to 70 billion U.S. dollars to help 36 countries
to move out from the grip of poverty.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that rich countries should have written off these
debts long ago but they waited until these poor countries were
almost "half dead" before they decided to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
