<HEADLINE> Malaysian Govt Supports Communications Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government will
continue to support the development of communications and Internet
infrastructure to facilitate more efficient and cost-effective
business transactions.
</P>
<P>
When closing the Microsoft Executive Summit '99 here Tuesday,
Energy, Communications and Multimedia Minister Datuk Leo Moggie
said the prospect to market goods and services to the fast-growing
number of Internet users in the country remains very bright.
</P>
<P>
The Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport, smart schools, cyber laws, the
Communications and Multimedia Act and the setting up of the
Communications and Multimedia Commission are to facilitate and
advance the growth of this sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These steps taken by the government are in recognition of the
importance and impact of technology and multimedia on the economy
today. Various measures have also been put in place by the
government to encourage Malaysians to embrace the power of
technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said local higher institutions of learning will supply some
25,000 local graduates in computer science, engineering, arts and
design, information technology (IT) and multimedia fields to meet
the need of the present 216 MSC-status companies for 35,000
skilled workers by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Moggie said the government welcomes companies such as Microsoft
with their technology, knowledge and experience to share with
business people their vision of how a networked environment can
transform Malaysian companies into living organisms with a digital
nervous system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
