<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
today's diplomatic news released by Xinhua:
</P>
<P>
Chinese NPC Chairman Hails Sino-Russian Cooperation
</P>
<P>
China's top legislator Li Peng said today that China is pleased
to see that Sino-Russian exchange and cooperation in politics,
economy, culture and other areas have been growing constantly, as
the two countries have forged an equal and mutually-trusting
partnership of strategic cooperation geared towards the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, made the remarks while meeting here this
afternoon with Oleg Korolyov, vice-chairman of Russia's Federation
Council, who is here for a two-day seminar on Sino-Russian
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
 DPRK and ROK Hold Vice-Ministerial Talks
</P>
<P>
Vice-ministerial talks between the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of Korea (ROK) began in Beijing
this morning, the first in 14 months, aimed at thrashing out both
military differences and establishing agreement on family reunions
on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, during the one and a half hours of talks
the two sides discussed a number of issues including the reunion
of separated families in the two parts of the Korean Peninsula,
the implementation of an agreement signed in 1991 on
reconciliation, non-aggression and cooperative exchanges between
the north and south of Korea, and the recent skirmishes involving
the two countries' navies in a disputed area of the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said at today
's routine press conference that China welcomes the talks and
hopes that progress would be made in the current talks.
</P>
<P>
China Refutes Allegation on Poverty-Relief Project
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the World Bank (WB) will grant loans to a
poverty-relief project in China's Qinghai Province as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue made the remarks here
today at a routine press briefing while denying the allegation
that China is aimed at assimilating Tibetans in this resettlement
project.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also urged the United States to take concrete steps to
better Sino-U.S. relations after the U.S.-led NATO attack on the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in early May.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side must be responsible for current situation of
bilateral relations," she said at the press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
