<HEADLINE> Indian General Elections to Be Held on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Indian Chief Election
Commissioner M. S. Gill said here Tuesday that the general
elections would be held on schedule in September this year and he
ruled out any possibility of postponement of the elections.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether there is any chance of delaying the polls
due to the fighting in Kargil of Kashmir with Pakistan, Gill said
at a press conference that the Election Commission was aware of
the complexities the country was facing but it had a
constitutional obligation to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has scheduled the general elections in
September this year. President K. R. Narayanan dissolved the 12th
lower house of Parliament on April 26 as no political party or
group could form a clear majority government after that led by
Atal Behari Vajpayee lost a confidence vote in the House.
According to the Indian constitution, the maximum gap between two
lower houses of Parliament could not be more than 180 days.
</P>
<P>
"The 12th Lok Sabha (Lower House of Parliament) has been
dissolved and we need to have the 13th Lok Sabha in place in good
time, that is by October 20," Gill said.
</P>
<P>
There is no provision in the constitution to postpone the
general elections throughout the country, another election
commissioner G. V. G. Krishnamurty said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
