<HEADLINE> Leading Scholar Passes Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Kang Yin, a leading scholar of
palaeography and seal cutting, research fellow of the capital
Normal University and a noted calligrapher, died of illness here
June 9, at the age of 73.
</P>
<P>
His remains were cremated today at the Babaoshan Cemetery for
Revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
Kang devoted his whole life to the research of China's ancient
writing and calligraphy and published some 20 works, including "A
Collection of Seal Impressions" he compiled after he spent 40
years on collecting dozens of thousands of China's ancient seals.
</P>
<P>
He is well-known in China and overseas for his inscriptions on
ancient bronze objects, bones or tortoise shells of the Shang
Dynasty (16th-11th century B.C.), seal calligraphy and seal
engraving.  
</P>
