<HEADLINE> Three Killed, 20 Missing in Sichuan Mud-rock Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A mud-rock flow which struck a
village in southwest China's Sichuan Province June 16 killed three
people and left 20 missing, according to members of a local rescue
team.
</P>
<P>
Ten other people were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The disaster buried six houses and destroyed ten others in
Longtanbao Village, Songpan County, in northern Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
The rescuers said that hopes of finding the missing people
alive are dim.
</P>
<P>
The mud-rock flow blocked the course of the Minjiang River, a
major tributary of the Yangtze River. The water level rose and
inundated a riverside highway, stranding some 1,000 tourists at a
nearby scenic spot.
</P>
<P>
A disaster-relief team led by a deputy governor of the province
carried out rescue work at the site. Highway transportation has
been resumed.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan's departments responsible for disaster-relief,
meteorological forecasting and water conservancy are on high alert
against possible floods along the Minjiang River, the Provincial
Disaster-Relief Office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
