<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Port Handles Less Cargo in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The inward cargo Hong Kong port
handled in the first quarter of 1999 dropped by eight percent to
23.9 million tons, and its outward cargo handled fell by 17
percent to 12.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the total cargo Hong Kong port handled in the
first quarter of 1999 decreased by 11 percent over a year earlier
to 36.8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
These are some of the statistics on ocean vessels, port cargo
and laden containers released by the Census and Statistics
Department here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the port cargo, seaborne cargo amounted to 28.5 million tons
which dropped by eight percent over a year earlier, while river
cargo contributed 8.3 million tons, representing a 21 percent
decrease.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1999, the port of Hong Kong handled 2.2
million TEUs seaborne laden containers and 0.4 million TEUs river
laden containers.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the first quarter of 1998, seaborne laden
containers showed a three percent decrease while river laden
containers dropped by four percent.
</P>
<P>
TEU stands for twenty-foot equivalent unit which is a unit
measure in capacity terms for different sizes of containers for
moving the cargo. One TEU is equivalent to the capacity of one 20'
x8'x8' container.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1999, 9,090 ocean vessels with a total
capacity of 50.3 million net registered tons (NRT) entered Hong
Kong. Compared with the first quarter of 1998, the number and
capacity of incoming ocean vessels decreased by 12 percent and
three percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
NRT is a unit measure in volume terms of the space of a vessel
available for carrying passengers or goods. One NRT is equivalent
to 100 cubic feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siberian Tiger Gives Birth to Triplets After Caesarean Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A 12-year-old Siberian tiger
living in the Tiger Garden of this capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province has given birth to triplets, following a
Caesarian operation.
</P>
<P>
Erhuan is one of ten rare Siberian tigers in the Shenyang
Tiger Garden. She had been 102 days pregnant when a team of
doctors from a local military hospital performed the operation
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Dr Jing Shuhua explained that the team made the decision to
perform the operation because it feared that the cubs might
otherwise be stillborn, since the middle-aged Erhuan had already
suffered the same tragedy twice before.
</P>
<P>
The operation, believed to have been the first of its kind ever
performed on a tiger, was successful, even though two of three
cubs were not breathing when they were born. A doctor performed
artificial respiration to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
Erhuan is recovering well from the operation, according to
workers at the Tiger Garden, who also found a dog to be the wet
nurse for the cubs.
</P>
<P>
The Siberian tiger is one of the rarest species on earth, with
a population estimated at about 200 in China, and fewer than 20 of
them living in the wild.
</P>
<P>
Tiger specialist Zang Zhubin said the successful performance of
the Caesarean operation was a further step in the efforts to
protect and help the rare creature to reproduce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
