<HEADLINE> Law To Curb Juvenile Delinquency Ready for Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A law aimed at curbing juvenile
delinquency will hopefully be passed by China's legislative body,
the Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (
NPC), after further discussions at a Standing Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The draft law is basically acceptable since many discussions
have been conducted and opinions solicited while an expert team
was organized to study the revision of the draft," Zhou Keyu, vice-
chairman of the NPC Law Committee, told the 10th Meeting of the
Ninth NPC Standing Committee which began here today.
</P>
<P>
"The law committee has advised that the responsibility for
preventing juvenile delinquency should rest on governments at all
levels, instead of simply "local governments" as stipulated in the
earlier version," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
"According to the revised draft, criminal activities by minors
may be investigated but the principle of 'education first,
punishment second' has to be considered," Zhou added.
</P>
<P>
"The law will also prohibit news reports, films, television
programs and publications from publishing the name, address,
photos or any damaging information about a juvenile who is
suspected of crimes before the case is finally judged," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
