<HEADLINE> Iranian FM: Street Name not Hurdle to Tehran-Cairo Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here on Tuesday that the name of a street in Tehran
should not become an obstacle in relations between Iran and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said at a press conference on the sideline of a
seminar on Caspian Sea that Iran and Egypt are currently holding
negotiations and making plans to upgrade their relations.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to a call made by some Egyptian
officials to change the name of a main street in northern Tehran
named after Khaled Islambuli, an Islamic extremist who
assassinated former Egyptian President Anwar Sadat after Egypt
signed a peace accord with Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri said
recently that the Iranian government can consider the proposal to
change the name in order to pave the way for a rapprochement
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, hardline Iranian newspapers soon blasted Nouri for his
 remark and some hardliners posted a big picture of Islambuli on a
building in the street last week to show their opposition to any
change.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi criticized the press for making a fuss about the issue
and said Iran-Egypt relations have greatly changed, especially in
the past two years and the two countries have satisfactory
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Iran severed its relations with Egypt after Egypt granted
asylum to Pahlavi, the former king of Iran, who was dethroned in
the 1979 Iranian Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been improved after
moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami adopted a detente
policy with other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
