<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Recast with Correction in 8th paragraph Macao Garrison Law To Be Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The draft Garrison Law for the
Macao Special Administrative Region, which was submitted to the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee today, is
expected to be passed by the committee's current meeting.
</P>
<P>
Experts say it is an important law concerning social stability
in Macao after it returns to China in the coming December.
</P>
<P>
The duties of the Macao garrison, according to the draft law,
include defense of the region, safeguarding of the region's
security, administration of military facilities, and undertaking
relevant military affairs concerning foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The garrison should not interfere in Macao's local affairs, but
the government of the special administrative region may request
the central government for the garrison's assistance in
maintaining public order and disaster relief in the region when
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The law also stipulates that the Macao garrison should be
commanded by the Central Military Commission and its composition
and the size of the force decided by the needs of the region's
defense, that the rank and file follow the laws of the special
administrative region as well as national ones, and personnel be
changed in fixed rotation, and that the expenses of the garrison
be paid by the central government.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts here said that the Macao garrison sent by the
central government will be a significant symbol of China's
resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Macao and will meet
the needs of safeguarding national unification and security and
defending the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
China is to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on
December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the current 10th meeting of the NPC Standing
Committee, the NPC Law Committee said that the ninth meeting of
the NPC Standing Committee in last April made preliminary
deliberations on the draft garrison law, and committee members
concurred on its feasibility.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Law Committee has made amendments to the
draft law based on the suggestions of some Standing Committee
members, specialists and Macao officials and public figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's PDI-P Maintains Lead With 34.05 Pct of Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) led by Megawati Soekarnoputri Tuesday continued
to lead over the other 47 parties in the vote counting of the June
7 election, grabbing 31.52 million votes.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results collected by the official
Antara News Agency from provincial chapters of the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI), the PDI-P garnered 34.05 percent of the
votes counted by Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by the ruling Golkar Party with 20.56 million
votes (22.22 percent), the National Awakening Party (PKB) with
12.43 million votes (13.43 percent), the United Development Party
(PPP) with 9.53 million votes (10.30 percent), the National
Mandate Party (PAN) with 6.4 million votes (6.92 percent), the
Crescent Star Party (PBB) with 1.75 million votes (1.90 percent)
and the Justice Party (PK) with 1 million votes (1.17 percent).
</P>
<P>
The data showed that by Tuesday afternoon, 39 of the 48
political parties contesting the June 7 election got less than 1
percent of the total votes counted.
</P>
<P>
A total of 92.58 million votes or 78.58 percent of the 117.8
million registered votes have been counted so far.
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P has so far been dominant in 11 provinces, namely
North Sumatera, South Sumatera, Bengkulu, Lampung, Jakarta, West
Java, Central Java, Yogyakarta, Bali, East Kalimantan and Central
Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
Golkar meanwhile took a lead in 14 provinces, namely West
Sumatera, Riau, Jambi, West Nusa Tenggara, East Nusa Tenggara,
East Timor, South Kalimantan, West Kalimantan, North Sulawesi,
South Sulawesi, Central Sulawesi, Southeast Sulawesi, Maluku and
Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
The PPP remained on top in the provisional tally in Aceh and
the PKB took a commanding in East Java.
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P also continued to be the front-runner in the
provisional tally of votes abroad with 8,882 votes, followed by
Golkar (5,167 votes), PKB (4,451), PAN (3,192) and PPP (2,344).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile official data collected by the General Election
Commission (KPU), based on votes counted till Tuesday afternoon
showed PDI-P in the lead with 21.7 million votes, followed by
Golkar (10.87 million), PKB (10.77 million), PPP (5.84 million)
and PAN (4 million).
</P>
<P>
KPU officials stressed that the results of the election will be
determined by the official data issued by KPU, and that other data
are unofficial.
</P>
<P>
KPU spokesman Djohermansyah Djohan said Tuesday that the KPU
will announce the final result of the election on July 8.
</P>
<P>
KPU member Andi A. Mallarangeng told reporters here Tuesday
that contestant parties in the election which receive less than 2
percent of the total ballots required for election to the House of
Representatives (DPR) will automatically be ousted from the
membership in the KPU.
</P>
<P>
"The law on the general election has clearly mentioned that
parties which get less than 2 percent of the vote cannot
participate in the next election. As a result, the party will
automatically lose its rights to sit in KPU membership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the June 7 election
to compete for 462 out of the 500 seats in the DPR. The remaining
38 seats are reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
