<HEADLINE> China to Revise Accountancy Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is going to revise and firm
up its existing Accountancy Law and will severely punish those who
infringe it.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng today outlined the draft of
the revised Accountancy Law and the draft of a list of related
punishments to the tenth meeting of the Ninth National People's
Congress Standing Committee which opened in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Xiang said that the existing law, which was approved by the
Ninth Meeting of the Sixth National People's Congress Standing
Committee in January of 1985, has played a positive role in
regulating and improving accountancy work in China, and has
contributed to the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
However, with the deepening of reforms and the development of
the socialist market economy, the law needs to be updated in order
to meet the demands of macroeconomic control by the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
The revised law will improve the basic systems and regulations
affecting business and expense accounting, strengthen the control
and inspection of accountancy practices and punish those who
violate the law.
</P>
<P>
Xiang said relevant organizations and some experts in criminal
law have worked out the list of punishments after careful studies
and research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
