<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Mayon Rains Ash, No Casualty Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' most active
volcano, Mayon, erupted Tuesday afternoon and rained ash on
surrounding areas, but no immediate casualties have been reported.
</P>
<P>
An expert of the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and
Seismology (Phivolcs) told Xinhua that the volcano erupted at
16:58 (08:58 GMT) and lasted about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Because the eruption is mild, and only lasted 10 minutes, no
casualties are expected," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a high column of ash and smoke were seen on
Mayon's crater, but the volcano already calmed down an hour after
its eruption.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Phivolcs has noted since May 13 the
activity of the volcano, which was characterized by intermittent
crater glow at the summit area and a slight increase in sulfur
dioxide emission.
</P>
<P>
He said that residents living near the volcano were reminded to
keep off the six-kilometer permanent danger zone, which means no
one should be within six kilometers of the volcano in any
direction.
</P>
<P>
Following the eruption, Mayon, which is about 330 kilometers
southeast of Manila, sent lava flowing down its southern flank and
rained ash on the surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Mayon, the most active volcano in the world, has erupted at
least 40 times since 1616. The volcano's last eruption on February
2, 1993, killed 78 people and affected 17,119 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
