<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open Military Port to International Shipping (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to open one of
its leading military ports, Huludao, in northeastern China's
Liaoning Province, to international commercial shipping later this
year, government sources announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Located on the Bohai Rim, Huludao ranks as an important port
for the Chinese naval forces, and one of the few bases for
developing and manufacturing advanced vessels in the nation.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of the Huludao port at this time indicates that
China will always take economic development as the first priority,
and ports with military facilities can be partly put into civil
use to spur regional economies," said Chen Zhengcai, a navigation
official with the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's cabinet, has given the green light
for the opening of the port, and preparations are being made and
are expected to be finished later this year for final opening
approval from the General Administration of Customs, according to
navigation officials in Huludao.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time for China to open a military port
for civil use and international shipping. Since the 1980s, China
has put into commercial use Dalian, Qingdao, Lianyungang,
Zhanjiang and Ningbo ports. All these ports are now leading parts
of the civil shipping system in China.
</P>
<P>
"Huludao port cannot match the other ports in cargo-handling
capacity, but its opening is an indication that China will never
stop the opening-up drive," Zhang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
