<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes over 2 Tons of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian army announced on Tuesday
that its forces seized 2,030 kilograms of opium Monday night in
arm clashes with drug smugglers in the southeastern border
province of Sistan-Baluchestan.
</P>
<P>
The army's 88th armored division also seized 13 camels, one
Klashinkov rifle and two rocket propeller grenade shells, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The division last week also confiscated five tons of different
types of narcotic drugs in the province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said over 10 tons of various narcotics have
been confiscated from smugglers in the province since the
beginning of the current Iranian calendar year, which started on
March 21.
</P>
<P>
Iran launched an anti-drug campaign in 1989 after the Majlis
(parliament) passed a law allowing capital punishment against drug
criminals. Over 195 tons of various narcotics were seized during
the past Iranian calendar year.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian army was deployed in the border provinces of
Sistan-Baluchestan and Khorasan last September following tensions
between Iran and the Afghan ruling Taliban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
