<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open Military Port to International Shipping (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the official, only domestic oceangoing freighters
will be allowed to enter Huludao port. And, as in former cases,
docks for commercial use in the port will be separated from the
naval docks and facilities.
</P>
<P>
Huludao port was first approved for opening to domestic
commercial shipping lines in 1984, and has since mainly handled
crude oil, oil products, grain and commodities for daily use
destined for the western part of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the opening of the Huludao port for
international shipping use could greatly boost the economy of the
western part of Liaoning, and it may also facilitate the
transportation of commodities, grain in particular, from the three
northeastern provinces and east part of Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
"If the Huludao port could be merged with the nearby Jinzhou
Port, whose current handling capacity stands at between six and
seven million tons, their advantages in shipping would be greatly
enhanced and the economy around the Bohai Rim would receive a
strong boost," said Ren Hong, a port planning official with the
State Development and Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Huludao has been a military port since 1908, when it was
constructed by the Qing Dynasty authorities, and later expanded in
1929 by General Zhang Xueliang. After the Japanese incursions into
northeast China in 1931, it was used by the Japanese army as a
transportation base.
</P>
<P>
The ice-free port now has an annual commercial handling
capacity of one million tons. The city government is moving to
expand it, with investment totaling 280 million yuan earmarked for
the first phase. One dock, with a handling capacity of 10,000 tons,
has already been completed, while two others -- of 20,000 dwt and
30,000 dwt capacity, respectively, are now under construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Mayon Volcano Erupts, No Immediate Casualty Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' most active
volcano, Mayon, rained ash on surrounding towns in the eastern
part of the country after its eruption Tuesday afternoon, but no
casualties have been reported so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and
Seismology (Phivolcs), the volcano, which is about 330 kilometers
southeast of Manila, erupted at 16:58 (08:58 GMT) and sent steam
lava flowing down its southern flank.
</P>
<P>
The Phivolcs noted that since May 13 the activity of the
volcano had been characterized by intermittent crater glow at the
summit area and a slight increase in sulfur dioxide emission.
</P>
<P>
The volcano's last eruption on February 2, 1993 killed 78
people and affected 17,119 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Bomber Freed From Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The IRA man who bombed to kill
former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984 was freed
Tuesday from the Maze Prison in Belfast after barely serving one
third of his recommended sentence.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Magee was given eight life sentences for the 1984
bombing of a hotel in Brighton, England, in an attempt to kill
Margaret Thatcher and her entire Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Five people were killed and 34 injured in the blast but
Thatcher escaped injury.
</P>
<P>
The trial judge recommended Magee serve a minimum of 35 years
in jail. But under the terms of the Good Friday Agreement, Magee
became eligible for early release after serving only about a third
of his sentence.
</P>
<P>
Magee is the 277th prisoner to be given early release under the
Good Friday Agreement, a landmark deal signed by Northern Ireland'
s feuding political groups in April 1998 aimed at ending 30 years
of violence.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Conservatives were outraged at Magee's early release,
saying it was a "particularly bad example". They urged the British
government to stop all early paramilitary prisoner releases until
terrorist arms decommissioning begins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
