<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Urged to Clear Cabinet Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has said the
delays by the Senate in clearing cabinet list could cripple the
new civilian government.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Doyin Okupe said Monday the delays were
sending wrong signals within and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the Senators to show some urgency "so that
government does not become unduly crippled."
</P>
<P>
However, Okupe expressed optimism that the Senate would keep to
the constitutional time-lag for screening.
</P>
<P>
The observation came four days to the expiration of the 21-day
 constitutional provision for the Senate to clear the nominees.
Failing to do this, they would seem to have been cleared.
</P>
<P>
Okupe advised that rather than delay the exercise, the Upper
House of Nigerian legislature could drop any of the nominees it
considers unfit.
</P>
<P>
On a separate topic, Okupe said the present administration has
no intention to marginalize the North or any section of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to reports in the media that the (Olusegun)
Obasanjo-led government is pursuing an "anti-North agenda", he
said the insinuations were false, illogical and difficult to
understand.
</P>
<P>
"President Obasanjo is a nationalist and will always be a
nationalist," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such sentiments, he said, were only being expressed by some few
elite which he described as vocal minority, who felt unnecessarily
threatened and could only fall back on ethnic or religious excuses
to explain their failures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
