<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Building Budget Gets Bigger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Spending on the Sydney 2000
Olympics rose by 40 million U.S. dollars on capital expenditure in
the latest New South Wales state budget, according to reports from
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
After a 265 million U.S. dollars rise in Olympic spending last
year, the New South Wales government intended to cut expenditure
to 123 million U.S. dollars in 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
But the figure in Tuesday's budget was nearly a third higher at
163 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In year-on-year terms it still represents a fall of about half
in spending on capital expenditure from the 315 million U.S.
dollars in 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Net cost to the NSW government of the Games has also risen by
28 million U.S. dollars to 1.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Michael Egan said 85 percent of the total venue and
infrastructure budget for the Olympics has been paid for, with 11
per cent to be spent this coming financial year.
</P>
<P>
The most recent economic assessment of the impact of the Games
estimates the Olympics will generate a total of 4.22 billion U.S.
dollars in additional economic activity and more than 90,000 new
jobs from 1994 to 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
