<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Mixed on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices closed mixed on
Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as gains failed to last long
because of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) inched up 2.85 points
to close at 2,123.23, off from the intraday high of 2,139.69
points.
</P>
<P>
Total volume contracted to 1,630.57 million shares worth
1,545.65 million Singapore dollars (906.33 million U.S. dollars).
Decliners outpaced advancers by 224 to 130 with 89 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The largest block was the 143.64 million shares parcel by
Hotung transacted at 0.595 U.S. dollars per share. It was followed
by Eagle which had 90.14 million units traded at a price of 0.49
U.S. dollars per unit. AFP was the next with 84.48 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS F headed the ascent of the day as it ran up 90 cents to
close at 19.70 Singapore dollars. SPH and SPH 100 gained 70 cents
each to finish at 28.70 and 28.80 Singapore dollars respectively.
DBS picked up 50 cents to end at 16.90 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On downside, BMT 100 plunged by 10 dollars to close at 80.00
Singapore dollars. CityDev sank 60 cents to finish at 11.20
Singapore dollars. OCBC lost 50 cents to end at 14.30 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said shares closed mixed with investors taking a
breather after the STI's sharp rise Monday.
</P>
<P>
They noted that some profit-taking in the afternoon evidently
dragged down the share prices.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, did not foresee a major pullback as the
economic recovery in Singapore and the region continued to weigh
on the market.
</P>
<P>
They noted U.S.-dollar denominated stocks continued to top the
actives list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
