<HEADLINE> Injury Forces O'Brien out of U.S. Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Dan O'Brien, the Olympic
champion and world-record decathlete, was forced to withdraw from
the U.S. athletics championships because of a foot injury, reports
said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
O'Brien will not take part in the meet, held in Eugene, Oregon,
from June 24-27, because of the injury to his left foot.
</P>
<P>
He won the gold medal in the decathlon in the 1996 Olympics,
holds the world record in the 10-event competition and is a three-
time world champion.
</P>
<P>
O'Brien, who turns 33 next month, said the International
Amateur Athletic Federation might grant him a wild-card invitation
that would allow him to compete for his fourth world championship
despite not participating in the U.S. event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
