<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Suspends S.Korean Tours to Mt. Kumgang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government has
ordered Hyundai Group to halt the operation of its cruise ships
which transport South Korean tourists to the Mountain Kumgang area
in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Monday night, the South Korean government convened an emergency
standing committee meeting of the National Security Council to
discuss the alleged DPRK's detention of South Korean female
tourist Monday and its consequences to the inter-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Unification Ministry identified the detained
as housewife Min yong-mi, 36, from Seoul.
</P>
<P>
"North Korean immigration officials detained her for a probe
into alleged abuse against the North. She is reported to have said
that North Korean defectors live well in the South," a ministry
spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK Central News Agency (KCNA) said Min made "ill-intended
remarks" to induce DPRK people to defect to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"Those who included a professional agent among tourists in an
attempt to preach defection must be condemned by the nation and
pay dearly for that," said the KCNA.
</P>
<P>
South Korean presidential secretary said Seoul decided to send
a message of strong protest to Pyongyang, while calling for Min's
immediate release.
</P>
<P>
The Mt. Kumkang tour began last November.
</P>
<P>
At present, the two Hyundai cruise ships, Pongnae and Pungak,
remain docked at the South Korean port of Tonghae, while the other
boat, Kumgang, is moored at the DPRK port of Changjon.
</P>
<P>
The detention occurred after the inter-Korean military clash
last Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
