<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Regulate Individual-Funded Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
National People's Congress (NPC), is deliberating a draft law
aimed at regulating solely individual-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The draft, designed also to protect investors and creditors,
was tabled for the second review at the 10th meeting of the NPC
Standing Committee, which convened here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xuwu, vice-chairman of the NPC Law Committee, said his
committee believed, after wide consultations in the past two
months, that it is necessary to have a law like this.
</P>
<P>
As the legislation intends to regulate enterprises solely
funded by individuals, the present title does not go well with the
contents. He suggested renaming it as "Individual's Solely-funded
Enterprise Law".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the widespread violations of workers' legitimate
rights and interests in solely-funded enterprises, Zhang said, "
Provisions aimed at protecting workers' rights and interests
should be included and the workers are entitled to set up trade
unions," he said.
</P>
<P>
As to the responsibility of the enterprises, Zhang suggested
the law stipulate that those enterprises solely funded by
household assets shoulder unlimited responsibility based on
household assets so as to protect the interests of creditors.
</P>
<P>
"The committee also believed that the law should not be applied
to foreign-funded enterprises as there is already legislation
dealing with this type of enterprises," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
