<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Consumer Prices Fall 4.0 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices of Hong Kong
registered a year-on-year rate of decrease of 4.0 percent in May,
after a 3.8 percent decline in April, according to the Census and
Statistics Department Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices are indicated by the Composite Consumer Price
Index (CPI). Similar movements were observed in the three sub-
indices, namely, the CPI(A), CPI(B) and Hang Seng CPI, that cover
respectively about 50 percent, 30 percent and 10 percent of
households.
</P>
<P>
In May 1999, the CPI(A), CPI(B) and Hang Seng CPI fell by 3.5
percent, 4.6 percent and 3.6 percent respectively over a year
earlier, somewhat larger than the corresponding decrease of 3.3
percent, 4.5 percent and 3.3 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by component, those consumer items registering year-on-
year rates of decrease in May 1999 included clothing and footwear,
durable goods, fuel and light, and housing.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, year-on-year rates of increase were recorded
for alcoholic drinks and tobacco, as well as transport.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that consumer prices
remained on an easing trend in May, along with the continuing
downward adjustment in costs and prices in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The further easing in price pressure was manifested in a wide
range of consumer goods and services, with the prevalence of price
discounts in the local retail market, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, import prices continued to be soft generally. On a
year-on-year comparison, the prices of clothing and footwear
showed the most significant decrease in May, followed by the
prices of consumer durables, charges for fuel and light, and
private housing rentals.
</P>
<P>
Compared with April, both the Composite CPI and CPI(A) showed
virtually no change in May. The CPI(B) fell by 0.2 percent, while
Hang Seng CPI rose by 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first five months of this year together, the
Composite CPI declined by 2.7 percent compared with the same
period in 1998. The corresponding decrease in the CPI(A), CPI(B)
and Hang Seng CPI were 2.3 percent, 3.3 percent and 2.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
