<HEADLINE> China to Reform Road Maintenance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China plans to launch a
nationwide restructuring of the maintenance of its 1.28 million
kilometer long highways including 8,700 kilometers of expressways.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhiqiang, director of the Road Department of the Ministry
of Communications, disclosed the government plan at today's Sino-
Britain Highway Maintenance and Management Symposium, which was
held in Changchun, the capital of northeastern Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the existing management of road
maintenance, mainly funded by the state, has been out of date and
should be replaced with a scientific and new system.
</P>
<P>
"The United Kingdom is advanced in maintenance management of
highways and some British experts have been invited to advise
their Chinese counterparts on the matter," Zhang noted.
</P>
<P>
Jilin has been a pioneer in China regarding such reform,
according to local officials. Since 1996, the province has
introduced an experimental system to let specialist companies, now
numbering 25, help maintain the state-owned roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
