<HEADLINE> China Drafts Meteorology Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to draw up a
meteorology law in a bid to regulate meteorological activities to
better serve national economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Wen Kegang, head of the National Meteorological Bureau,
delivered the draft law to the 10th session of the National People
's Congress Standing Committee, which convened here today.
</P>
<P>
"Meteorology plays a major role in disaster prevention and
improving agricultural production and ensuring defense," Wen said.
</P>
<P>
"China already has a series of rules and regulations concerning
meteorology but they are insufficient to deal with the new
situations and problems that have arisen during the rapid economic
growth and rising demand for services," he said.
</P>
<P>
There exist an overlapping of equipment and facilities, reduced
accuracy of meteorological forecasts, unauthorized issuing of
disastrous weather warnings and waste of meteorological resources.
</P>
<P>
The draft, made up of eight chapters and 43 items, deals with
the construction and management of meteorological facilities and
forecasts, disaster prevention and the development and protection
of meteorological resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
