<HEADLINE> Australia Looking Forward to New Truffle Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Tasmania state is
expecting to add to its reputation with a new industry and a
source of fine food as the first black truffle, a kind of precious
underground fungus, was found in the state.
</P>
<P>
A dog called Pip sniffed out the first black truffle from the
base of a hazelnut tree in northern Tasmania last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Australian Associated Press said Tuesday that "Pip sniffed out
a new truffle industry."
</P>
<P>
Black truffle is a traditional product of France, especially in
Perigord region, and its price is over 1,300 U.S. dollars a kilo.
</P>
<P>
Joined with farmers, the France Industry of Perigord Truffles
of Tasmania has planted 25 plantations of specially inoculated
hazelnut trees during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
Truffle produced in Tasmania will be sold to the gourmet
restaurants of Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Premier of Tasmania State Jim Bacon looked and sniffed the
first truffle Monday night saying that a truffle industry would
add to Tasmania's reputation as a source of fine good. 
</P>
</TEXT>
