<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds No Dioxin Contaminated Forage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China has found no dioxin
contaminated forage so far, according to an official from the
Ministry of Agriculture today.
</P>
<P>
Jia Youling, director of the ministry's animal husbandry
department, pointed out that China did not import forage from
Belgium, Germany, Holland, and France, which have all reported
dioxin contamination since January.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that China has carefully checked its fodder imports
and manufacturing after a report highlighting the European scare
was published.
</P>
<P>
The dioxin panic started when some Belgian chickens and eggs
were found to be contaminated with dioxin and this later spread to
pork and milk.
</P>
<P>
Short-term exposure of humans to high levels of dioxins may
result in skin lesions, and altered liver functions, while long-
term exposure is linked to impairment of the immune system.
</P>
<P>
Jia also noted that the dioxin contaminations in Europe are
reported to be caused by the forage added with animal fat or oil
for industrial use. In China, only 25 percent of fodder comes from
fodder processing plants. The country does not have a tradition of
adding animal fat to fodder.
</P>
<P>
He noted China has paid great attention to the contamination of
forage and put into effect a regulation on the management of
fodder and fodder additives on May 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
