<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Growth in Exports by Overseas-Funded Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Exports by overseas-funded
businesses in China grew for the first five months of this year,
despite a fall in the nation's overall export volume during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that the overseas-funded ventures
exported 31.9 billion U.S. dollars worth of products in the five
months, an increase of 5.77 percent over the same period in 1998,
while China's overall exports dropped by five percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the sector also expanded 4.36 percent to 30.75
billion U.S. dollars during the period. The value of equipment and
goods imported as investments, however, dropped 31.09 percent to 4.
15 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of general products by overseas-funded enterprises grew
16.6 percent to 4.32 billion U.S. dollars in the first five months,
with imports of such products growing a massive 89 percent to 5.7
billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Garrison Law To Be Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The draft Garrison Law for the
Macao Special Administrative Region, which was submitted to the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee today, is
expected to be passed by the committee's current meeting.
</P>
<P>
Experts say it is an important law concerning social stability
in Macao after it returns to China in the coming December.
</P>
<P>
The duties of the Macao garrison, according to the draft law,
include defense of the region, safeguarding of the region's
security, administration of military facilities, and undertaking
relevant military affairs concerning foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The garrison should not interfere in Macao's local affairs, but
the government of the special administrative region may request
the central government for the garrison's assistance in
maintaining public order and disaster relief in the region when
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The law also stipulates that the Macao garrison should be
commanded by the Central Military Commission and its composition
and the size of the force decided by the needs of the region's
defense, that the rank and file follow the laws of the special
administrative region as well as national ones, and personnel be
changed in fixed rotation, and that the expenses of the garrison
be paid by the central government.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts here said that the Macao garrison sent by the
central government will be a significant symbol of China's
resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Macao and will meet
the needs of safeguarding national unification and security and
defending the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
China is to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on
December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the current 12th meeting of the NPC Standing
Committee, the NPC Law Committee said that the ninth meeting of
the NPC Standing Committee in last April made preliminary
deliberations on the draft garrison law, and committee members
concurred on its feasibility.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Law Committee has made amendments to the
draft law based on the suggestions of some Standing Committee
members, specialists and Macao officials and public figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reduce Crude Oil Production Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China has plans to continue its
efforts to bring down the production cost of crude oil by five
percent this year, a senior official from the China National
Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) announced today.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction will be realized by shutting down debt-ridden
oil exploration wells and cutting off the output of crude oil
where costs exceeds international prices," said Ma Fucai, general
manager of CNPC.
</P>
<P>
The company's crude oil production costs dropped to 587 yuan
per ton last year, the lowest for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
CNPC has targeted an output reduction of 1.2 million tons of
crude oil this year from last year's amount of 107 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"The restructuring of the country's oil and petrochemical
sectors, completed in 1998, enabled CNPC to integrate exploration,
development and processing, domestic and international trade, and
production and marketing in order to effectively optimize
distribution," according to Ma.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges U.S. to Create Friendly Environment for Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China today urged the United
States to take concrete steps to better Sino-U.S. relations after
U.S.-led NATO attacked the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in early
May.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side must be responsible for current situation of
bilateral relations," Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhang Qiyue said
at a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government must give full recognition to the serious
nature of the attack incident, give serious attention to the
Chinese government's solemn position and demands, conduct a
comprehensive and thorough investigation and severely punish the
perpetrators, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government must give a satisfactory account and
explanation to the Chinese government and people, Zhang said while
commenting on the U.S. government's report on the investigation
into the embassy bombing, which presented by U.S. Undersecretary
of State Thomas R. Pickering on June 16.  
</P>
