<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will take part in an international fair in
Mozambique from August 30 to September 5, the head of Egypt's
International Exhibitions and Markets Authority said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed al Saeed Saleh said Egyptian companies will exhibit
consumer goods, car spare parts and other commodities,
which he said meet the requirements of the Mozambican market.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's participation in the Mozambican fair, the first of its
kind, conforms with its policy to open new African markets in a
bid to promote exports, Saleh added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Germany have signed two contracts for the
construction of power stations, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under one of the contracts signed here on Sunday, Germany will
provide Egypt with about 89 million U.S. dollars for launching the
first stage of the El-Zafarana station designed to generate
electricity with wind power.
</P>
<P>
Under the other contract,
Germany will provide engineering and consulting services for the
building of the El-Kurimat station in the Red Sea area, to be
operated with solar energy during the day and natural gas at
night.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Kuwaiti Fund for Economic Development will offer
Egypt an easy-term loan of about 88 million dollars to help Egypt
reclaim 168,000 hectares of land in northern Sinai, the Egyptian
Gazette newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed here on Sunday, the loan will be
repaid at an interest rate of 3 percent in 25 years with a
five-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti fund has so far provided Egypt with 917 million
dollars in loan, including 153 million dollars for the land
reclamation scheme in northern Sinai.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran announced on Monday to grant free landing at
Tehran's Mehrabad international airport to all foreign cargo
planes except Israeli ones as of the day.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Civil Aviation Organization said in a statement
that foreign airlines are required to make coordination with
the Mehrabad airport at least 24 hours earlier to use cargo
services.
</P>
<P>
The crew of the planes will be given transit visas, the
statement said, adding the Iranian customs office at the airport
will carry out formalities in the minimum of time.
</P>
<P>
The Isfahan airport in central Isfahan province will give
the same services to the cargo planes if the traffic at
Mehrabad airport became heavy, it added.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The growth rate of Iran's gross national products
(GNP) has dropped to less than 2 percent in the past Iranian
calendar year ending March 20, an Iranian economic official
announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director of Foreign Exchange Credit Allocation Department of
the Central Bank of Iran (CBI) Gholamreza Nadali Ataabadi said
that the GNP growth rate was registered at 5.1 percent at the
beginning of the second five-year economic development plan from
1995 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar in Sari, northern Mazadaran province, he
put average GNP growth rate over the past four years at 3.5
percent, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ataabadi said that the country's inflation soared to about
19.7 percent last Iranian year from 12.4 percent at the
beginning of the second five-year plan period.
</P>
<P>
On average, the inflation rate was about 25 percent over
the past four years, he said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egypt-Netherlands day for trade and investment was
inaugurated Monday in a bid to promote the economic ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Netherlands Ambassador to Egypt Ronald Loudon told the
inaugural ceremony that his country imported 147 million dollars
worth of Egyptian goods in 1998, 100 percent more than 1997.
</P>
<P>
Loudon said the Netherlands is the third largest importer of
Egyptian goods in Europe and Egypt's third largest investor after
the United States and Britain in the world.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- Director of the National Audit Bureau of the
Palestinian Central Statistics Department Ghania Tijani has
disclosed that gross domestic product of the Palestinian territory
in 1997 amounted to some 4.2 billion dollars and gross national
incomes stand at 4.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tijani said at a recent news conference that gross national
incomes include revenues of Palestinians employed in Israel as
well as remittances received by Palestinian residents of the West
Bank and Gaza from abroad, the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Students Take Entrance Exams for Study in Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 759 middle school
students in Macao Tuesday morning began their three-day entrance
exams for studying in institutions of higher learning in the
mainland areas of China.
</P>
<P>
Coming from more than 20 middle schools, the students are
striving for 56 specialties in 71 universities and colleges on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
The number of examinees is the largest in recent years,
according to Ng Va Kai, vice director of the Macao Chinese
Education Association.
</P>
<P>
He noted that more and more Macao students are aiming at
entering institutions in north China and northeast China in
addition to those located in south China and east China.
</P>
<P>
With Macao's return to the motherland around the corner,
frequent tours to the mainland have enabled Macao students to know
more about the mainland, Ng Va Kai said, adding that those who
completed their studies in colleges or universities on the
mainland found work more easily in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ng attributed the increasing number of examinees
to the fact that colleges and universities on the mainland have
better teaching quality and lower expenses than similar studies in
Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
