<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Draft 10th Five-Year Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's 10th Five-Year Plan for
2001-2005, which is currently being drafted, will have major
differences with the former nine five-year plans and will be
implemented in line with shaping a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
"The contents, form and roles of the medium- and long-term
outline will have profound changes taking into account modern
demands, especially in the way the market has a basic role in
resources distribution," said Zeng Peiyan, minister in charge of
the State Development Planning Commission, at a televised
conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
"The new plan must rely on market forces while also guiding and
regulating the market," Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
Economic development and population growth are having an
negative impact on the shortage of resources facing China.
Therefore, the new plan should not simply focus on increasing
investments and launching new projects for rapid development as it
has been done before, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He urged relevant departments and localities to do their best
in giving helpful suggestions for drafting the plan.
</P>
<P>
He told planners that they should take into account both the
domestic and international situation when formulating the plan,
stressing that governments at all levels should not be involved in
commercial activities but leave those activities to enterprises
and marketers.
</P>
<P>
Zeng called for more attention to be paid to the central and
western areas, especially the latter, in a move to narrow the East-
West gap. Priority should be given to projects related to water
conservancy, electricity, communications, environmental protection
and the development of resources in the western part of the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"More democracy is needed in drafting the plan in an attempt to
reflect and protect the interests of major market players," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNC, DPRK Meet for Tension Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the United
Nations Command (UNC) and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) met Tuesday at the truce village of Panmunjom to
discuss measures on tension reduction caused by the inter-Korean
conflict in the Yellow Sea last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The talks were frank, open and useful to both sides, "said a
UNC release issued after the two-hour talks.
</P>
<P>
"The primary objective of the meeting was to reduce tensions in
the Yellow Sea," said UNC spokesman Carl Kropf.
</P>
<P>
The UNC and the DPRK held talks on June 15, but the meeting
ended with no results and saw the two sides trade a verbal war on
who fired first during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the UNC proposed measures to reduce tensions
and to avoid escalation of conflict, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The measures include that the DPRK ships operate north of the
Northern Limit Line and the South Korean vessels south of the line
and the two sides improve communication channels in the vicinity
of the Northern Limit Line.
</P>
<P>
"The UNC also proposed to meet again in the general office
forum to continue dialogue on these recommended steps," said the
release.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting was the seventh of its kind between the two
sides aimed at reducing tension on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
In the inter-Korean military conflict on June 15, a DPRK
torpedo boat was sunken and three others badly damaged while two
South Korean ships were slightly damaged.
</P>
<P>
In the conflict, 30 DPRK servicemen were reportedly killed
whereas nine South Koreans were injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
