<HEADLINE> Israel Investigates Violence of Policemen, Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police will open
investigation over the use of rubber-bullets by policemen in a
demonstration Monday night, during which Arab Israeli legislator
Azmi Bishara was injured, Israel Radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eight people, including Bishara, were injured Monday evening as
police fired rubber bullets to disperse about 200 demonstrators
protesting against the demolition of an Arab house in the northern
city of Lod.
</P>
<P>
Police officials said they will investigate whether the use of
rubber bullets was necessary.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the police of intentionally aiming to injure, Bishara
said he will demand an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli army will exam its responsibility in a
murder case by returning the confiscated gun to a 26-year-old
soldier who had violence tendency.
</P>
<P>
The gun of Verto Ababa was confiscated as a woman complained to
the army that Ababa threatened her life and that of her family's
after she refused to marry him. But the gun was later returned to
him.
</P>
<P>
The soldier shot and killed the woman and her two children, and
then killed himself Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his coming
successor Ehud Barak voiced shock at the murder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
