<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Insurers Pass Y2K Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A recent test shows that major
insurance firms in China have basically solved the year 2,000
problem which could affect their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
The China Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC) said in a
press release today that all the 13 Chinese insurance firms
participating in the test conducted last Saturday and Sunday have
proved their readiness for the year 2,000 computer bug, also known
as Y2K or the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
During the test, the insurance firms halted all business
activities and adjusted their computer systems to several dates
when Y2K is likely to attack.
</P>
<P>
The CIRC said all the firms passed the test without system
breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
Two other major tests are scheduled to be carried out on July
17-18 and September 18-19.
</P>
<P>
None of the overseas insurance firms operating in China took
part in the test, as CIRC sources said they would tackle the Y2K
problem by themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0151 </DOCNO>
