<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investors Play Bigger Role in High-Tech Industry in Southern Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investors have become a
major part of this south China city's high-tech industrial
development, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
It now has 130 high-tech companies, 60 percent of which are
backed by overseas investors and overseas investment accounts for
55.7 percent of the city's total high-tech research, development,
and production funds. Overseas-backed enterprises contributed 70
percent of Shenzhen's high-tech product exports last year.
</P>
<P>
Many overseas investors have chosen Shenzhen to produce
computers and related software, telecommunications equipment,
audio-video goods, electro-mechanical products, new chemical
materials, and bioengineering products that involve a lot of
technology and capital and this has improved the city's industrial
structure, a local official says.
</P>
<P>
The city will continue to improve its investment environment
and find ways to introduce overseas investment into a wider range
of production.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong Province, which is just
north of Shenzhen, non-government enterprises have been playing a
greater role in its high-tech industry. Guangzhou now has 225 high-
tech enterprises, 147 of which are non-government ones.
</P>
<P>
To increase its high-tech industrial development, the city will
set aside a billion yuan to apply high-tech developments and to
help high-tech companies repay bank loans or reinvest and to
provide financial guarantees through next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
