<HEADLINE> Manila Starts Process of Recovering More Marcos Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has begun
the process of recovering the 100 million U.S. dollar Swiss
accounts under the name of five Marcos cronies, a senior official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora
confirmed reports that the Marcos cronies' accounts have been
identified, but he cautioned against raising high hopes for the
immediate recovery of the money stashed in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
"That means they've identified some accounts, but I wouldn't
wait for it tomorrow or the day after. This is going to take a
while," he said, recounting the tedious process that the
government had to go through to effect the transfer of the 590
million dollar escrow account from Swiss banks to the Philippine
National Bank (PNB).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an unnamed source at the Presidential Commission on
Good Government (PCGG) was quoted as saying the Swiss authorities
identified last month several secret Swiss accounts under the name
of five close friends of the late president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said that the recovery of the funds requires that the
government "go through a fairly extended count procedure to make
sure that these are really ill-gotten."
</P>
<P>
"That's one of the requirements, both of the Swiss authorities
and Philippine courts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said, the government is happy to note that the
 recovery process has now begun, adding that "it is definitely
possible" for the government to gain control of the 100 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
