<HEADLINE> North-South Korean Talks Open in Beijing (Details Added) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yang Young-Sik, vice minister of National Unification who led
the delegation of the Republic of Korea (ROK), greeted the
delegation of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
headed by Pak Yong-Su, vice director-general of the Committee for
Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland.
</P>
<P>
The two sides shook hands and exchanged name-lists of delegates,
who were officially appointed respectively by the ROK Ministry of
National Unification and the DPRK Committee of Peaceful
Reunification of the Fatherland.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, during the one and a half hours of talks
the two sides discussed a number of issues including the reunion
of separated families in the two parts of the Korean Peninsula,
the implementation of an agreement signed in 1992 on
reconciliation, non-aggression and cooperative exchanges between
the north and south of Korea, and the recent skirmishes involving
the two countries' navies in a disputed area of the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the two sides "repeatedly" reiterated their
respective stances on the recent skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to telephone each other to set the
schedule for their second meeting.  
</P>
