<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Reviews Public-Bidding Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, which
convened here today, started its second review of the draft public-
bidding law aimed at curbing corruption in the building sector.
</P>
<P>
Gu Angran, vice-chairman of the Law Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), reported today on the draft to the 10th
meeting of the NPC Standing Committee on the draft legislature.
</P>
<P>
Since the draft's first review at the last session in April,
the committee has solicited opinions from a wide section of the
society. "We hold that it is very necessary to have a law like
this now," Gu said.
</P>
<P>
"As they will be the basic rules for bidding procedures, the
legislation should apply not only to the construction sector, but
also to bidding in other activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
All projects, whether they are wholly or partially financed by
the public, should be subjected to public biddings according to
the law, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"As to whether the projects could be partitioned or sub-
contracted, the committee believed that the non-essential parts
could be contracted out according to agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And both the bidders and sub-contractors shoulder the
responsibility for project quality," he noted.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth completion of projects and their quality,
the committee suggested that the law should adopt the universal
practice of a financial guarantee which is levied on the bidders
and contractors. "This means that if they can't fulfill their
agreements, the guarantees can be confiscated and any losses can
be accounted for," Gu said.
</P>
<P>
The committee also suggested that those bidders who fail to
fulfill agreements should not be allowed to bid in the future and
even have their commercial licenses revoked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
