<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Liberalization of Internet Exchange Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Telecommunication Authority
of Singapore will open up the market of international Internet
exchange service in Singapore as another step towards achieving
its goal of becoming an Internet hub and information society.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Communications and Information Technology Yeo
Cheow Tong made the announcement in his address at the opening
ceremony Tuesday for the telecommunication exhibition CommunicAsia
99.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said the move to allow more providers of Internet exchange
service in Singapore will enhance Singapore's attractiveness as a
portal for high speed access to the Internet backbone.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the Asian Internet Access Service Providers
(IASPs) will also have more means to interconnect via Singapore
and this will encourage the development of an intra-Asian Internet
network," Yeo said.
</P>
<P>
Internet exchanges are physical interconnection sites for IASPs
to access the global Internet backbone and exchange traffic with
one another. Such exchanges will enable IASPs traffic to be
aggregated before being sent via leased circuits to the U.S.
Internet backbone and the regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeo also billed information and communications technology (ICT)
as the key driver and transformer in the net economy and
information society of the future and said that his ministry is in
the midst of formulating the ICT21 Master Plan to facilitate the
development of ICT in Singapore over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"Our vision is to transform Singapore into a dynamic and
vibrant global ICT capital with a thriving and prosperous net
economy by the year 2010," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
He said the ICT21 Master Plan will map out strategies to attain
three key objectives which include developing the ICT sector as
the key sector of growth in Singapore's Economy, using ICT as a
common platform to boost the performance of Singapore's
knowledge-based economy and leveraging on ICT to enhance the
quality of life and standard of living of Singaporeans in the
information society of the future.
</P>
<P>
Some 900 companies from 40 countries and regions participate in
the CommunicAsia 99 which will last to June 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
