<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Officials Leave for Congo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- South African government
officials left for Zambia Tuesday morning for talks aimed at
resolving the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Foreign affairs director-general Jackie Selebi heads the South
African mission, which will be followed by a ministerial team
expected to depart for Lusaka Wednesday or early Thursday, the
South African Press Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial delegation will comprise of Deputy Foreign
Minister Aziz Pahad, Provincial Affairs and Local Government
Minister Sydney Mufamadi and Defense Minister Patrick Lekota.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma said Sunday that she saw the
resolution of the conflict in Congo (K) as one of the top
priorities in her new portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said unless the conflict in Africa was resolved there was
no possibility of a renaissance on the continent.
</P>
<P>
She said although the latest initiative to bring about peace in
Congo (K)

was being led by Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, South Africa
was giving the process its full support.
</P>
<P>
"We would like a cease-fire in the DRC and a standstill of
foreign troops, and (to see) the Congolese beginning a meaningful
dialog to resolve the problems there," she said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was involved in talks with all the countries
sucked in the Great Lakes conflict including the warring parties
in the DRC, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of countries involved in the Congo (K) crisis met in
Pretoria last week after they attended Thabo Mbeki's inauguration
as South Africa's new president Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki told a media conference that the Lusaka meeting was
expected to put forward proposals for a ceasefire in the DRC
conflict between rebels wanting to topple President Laurent
Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, preliminary talks to prepare for a regional peace
summit on the DRC failed to get under way Monday because some of
the delegates had not yet arrived, a Zambian official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Some officials have not yet arrived for the meeting and we are
all waiting for them...it's possible that the meeting might take
place on Tuesday," Agence France Presse quoted the official, who
declined to be named, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Sunday that the DRC peace talks would begin at the
 officials' level on Monday, followed by a ministerial meeting
possibly on Wednesday through to Friday.
</P>
<P>
Depending on the outcome of the two meetings, a summit of heads
of state involved in the Congolese conflict would be called on
Saturday to sign a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Tutsi rebels -- disaffected soldiers and opposition politicians
-- backed by Rwanda and Uganda, launched an insurgency in the
eastern Congo 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Kabila sought military support from other African nations such
as Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The rebels now control roughly the eastern part of the vast
central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
