<HEADLINE> FM Spokeswoman Refutes Allegation on China's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue made the
remarks here today at a regular press conference while denying
the allegation that China is aimed at assimilating Tibetans in
this resettlement project.
</P>
<P>
 Certain western media and a few Tibetan splitist groups
recently asked the World Bank to reject or delay the approval of
granting loans to the project.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the project is part of the poverty-relief program
implemented by Qinghai Province to uproot poverty in the land-
locked province.
</P>
<P>
"The mission of the project is to remove a portion of the poor
population from their current living areas, where natural
conditions are so harsh that development cannot be realized, to
Dulan County of Haixi Prefecture in western Qinghai, where natural
conditions are relatively better," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Local residents from all ethnic groups, including Tibetans,
thus can shake off poverty and local socio-economic development
can also be improved," she said, adding that the Chinese
government has placed high importance on improving the living
standards of all ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
A three-year feasibility study has been carried out on the
project, which is supported by local people, she said.
</P>
<P>
Many countries participating in the financing of the project
agreed that the project conforms to the standard of WB loans, she
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
