<HEADLINE> Air And Landscape Remain Fine in Southern Chinese Tourist City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The city of Guilin in China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region had 2.48 million tourists in the
first four months, up 9.26 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Overseas tourists accounted for 148,000, up 50 percent. Guilin
is known for its picturesque landscape and scenery and many
distinguished guests from abroad, including a great number of
heads of state like U.S. President Bill Clinton, have visited the
city.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Xinmin, the head of its tourism administration, says that
improved environment has helped the city's tourism boom.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the city has moved 49 polluting factories
out of the city and has spent 56 million yuan on afforestation and
beautifying the banks of the Li River and installing a marsh-gas-
energy network in areas around the river to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of the industrial waste water and garbage
are treated and gas is used for cooking in 87 percent of the city'
s households.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to these measures, the city's people can breathe air
that is free of smoke and dust and the forest coverage is 36.5
percent, higher than the national average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
