<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Punish Futures-Related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
National People's Congress (NPC), is mulling over a draft
resolution designed to regulate the futures market and severely
punish futures related crimes.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jingyu, director of the Legislative Affairs Office of the
State Council, delivered the draft to the 10th meeting of the NPC
Standing Committee, which convened here today.
</P>
<P>
"Though the country's Criminal Law contains provisions
concerning securities, it does not deal directly with crimes
related to futures," Yang said in his explanation to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
China's futures market, which was piloted in 1990, experienced
rapid expansion in the following years. "Despite the tightening up
of regulations and clearing up of anomalies, there still exist
problems," Yang added.
</P>
<P>
They include the unauthorized establishment of futures
exchanges, insider trading, the concocting of false information to
disrupt the markets, price manipulation and unauthorized trading
on overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
"These and other negative activities have damaged the interests
of investors and severely disrupted the financial and economic
order," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
"The futures' market can't operate healthily unless these
crimes are punished," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The State Council intends to ask the NPC Standing Committee to
expand the scope of a number of items of the Criminal Law and make
futures-related crimes punishable under the law, Yang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
