<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Cousin Leads a Happy Life in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The four-room flat has beautiful
Tibetan-style furniture, electric appliances, a small area for
studying the sutras, and a Buddhist niche in the wall with
offering bowls and a butter lamp.
</P>
<P>
It's a lot smaller than where they lived when she was a young
girl, says Galsang Zhoima, a cousin of the Dalai Lama, "but it is
very warm, comfortable, and cozy." The 51-year old woman, whose
mother and the Dalai Lama's mother are sisters, now lives in the
Chengguan District of Lhasa, Tibet' capital.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima and her brother, were brought to Lhasa by the Dalai Lama,
after he visited them in 1955 in Huangzhong County in Qinghai
Province where he was born. He then fled to India in 1959 after a
failed rebellion against the central government.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima's father, died in 1990 after living in India for ten
years. Her elder brother is an engineer with an institute in Lhasa
and her younger brother is a section director with the Public
Health Department. Both have been to India to visit relatives.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima used to work at a sewing cooperative. In 1984, she was
elected a member of the district People's Political Consultative
Conference and later became a deputy of the National People's
Congress. She often visits urban and rural units and ordinary
families and submits proposals to the regional People's Political
Consultative Conference or People's Congress. She has traveled to
Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and many other major cities
and says, "Over the past four decades, Tibet has experienced
tremendous changes with the help of the central government and
other provinces, even though it still lags behind many areas."
</P>
<P>
In 1969, Zhoima married Zhezhu Wangdui who is 10 years older
and used to be a lama. The couple have a daughter who is a tour
guide and a son who is a lama. Zhoima says she is satisfied with
her life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Competitiveness Ranks 29th by IMD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China was ranked 29th in term of
economic competitiveness among all nations of the world this year
by the International Institute for Management Development (IMD), a
local newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ranking was made according to 244 indexes related to a
nation's economic development, resources and environment, the
International Business Daily says.
</P>
<P>
The IMD released the rankings in its World Competitiveness
Yearbook. China was listed 28th in 1998.
</P>
<P>
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region was ranked at
7th place this year, dropping from the 3rd place last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the yearbook reports that Hong Kong's economic
situation is still outstanding after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Singapore stayed at the top two places
for two years running, while Finland and the Netherlands jumped to
the 3rd and 5th places respectively. They ranked 9th and 7th last
year.
</P>
<P>
This is the tenth year that the IMD has made such rankings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
