<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coins Provide Evidence Of Japanese Invasion of  China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Jiangdongmen Memorial Hall in
Jiangsu Province, which was built to commemorate the victims of
the Nanjing Massacre, has 2 copper coins that reveal Japan's
intent to occupy China 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The coins were given by an overseas Chinese in the United
States. They weigh 100 grams each and are 4.5 centimeters in
diameter. On the obverse side of one coin is a picture of a
Japanese officer with a sabre at his waist and a pair of
binoculars in his hands and 3 Japanese soldiers in a shooting
stance.
</P>
<P>
The reverse side has three Japanese military planes and a bomb,
on which are inscribed the Chinese characters "in commemoration of
the China incident". In the background is the Great Wall and a map
with the cities of Beijing, Xi'an, Qingdao, Jinan, Nanjing, and
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The other coin has pictures of Japanese military attacks in
China. Specialists have confirmed that the coins were made by a
Japanese mint in 1937 to commemorate Japan's invasion of China and
say that the maps and names of major cities clearly reveal the
intent of Japanese military forces to conquer China.
</P>
<P>
According to other historical records, including Japanese
records, at least 300,000 Chinese were butchered and more than 20,
000 women raped in December of 1937 in Nanjing, Jiangsu's capital,
by the Japanese invaders in "the Rape of Nanking", which was later
called "a dark page in modern civilization" by historians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tests Food Imports from EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Health Ministry has
dispatched its food inspectors to collect a number of imported
foodstuffs from the European Union from supermarket shelves for
tests as a food and soft drinks poisoning scare hit some Nairobi
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Bureau of Standards (KBS) Monday declared a ban on
all chicken, eggs, pork and meat products from the EU ahead of a
final government decision, the state-run Kenya Times newspapers
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
KBS import inspection officials were put on alert to ensure
that foodstuffs and drinks containing the cancer-causing dioxin
are not allowed into Kenya from the EU member states exporting
such products manufactured in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
However, a source from the Health Ministry said the ministry
could not recommend any action by the government before tests on
the foodstuffs and soft drinks under scrutiny are finalized and
results determined.
</P>
<P>
Spot checks at a number of supermarkets in Nairobi revealed
that most of the snacks, chocolates and biscuits are imported from
Belgium, Switzerland, France, Italy and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Following the dioxin scare, the KBS has subsequently instructed
its officials to reject all coca-cola products from Belgium,
France, Luxemburg and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The KBS quality assurance officials are also carrying out local
market surveillance for all imported chicken, eggs, pork, meat
and coca-cola products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
