<HEADLINE> Urban Population Explosion Causes Problems: Moi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Urban planning in developing
countries has been hampered by the explosive urban population
growth coupled with shortage of resources for adequate services,
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has admitted.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Times newspaper Tuesday quoted Moi as saying that in
many developing nations, a large proportion of urban dwellers
remained deprived of basic services such as proper housing, clean
water supply, sanitation and access to health care.
</P>
<P>
Urban areas no longer guarantee a better standard of living as
many of those seeking refuge from the worsening conditions of
poverty in the rural areas find themselves caught up in equally
dehumanizing conditions of poverty in the cities, said Moi Monday
at the opening of U.S.-Africa Sister Cities Conference in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged the conference to work and come up
with workable solutions to some of the urbanization problems
facing developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In the Kenyan capital Nairobi, about 50 percent of people live
in only five percent of residential areas without adequate
housing, water supply and health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
