<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing High Quality Stone Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- After 2 decades of growth, China
plans to slow stone products output down while increasing their
quality.
</P>
<P>
Better quality stone products will account for 90 percent of
output in the next 15 years and annual growth of stone production
will be held to 10 percent, according to Zhang Wenbo, of the China
Stone Products Association. Zhang is on an investigation tour of
the region.
</P>
<P>
China has become the world's second largest stone producer
since the 1980s, but high grade products account for only 35
percent of the output. It produces 130 million square meters of
stone annually, most of it from Fujian, Shandong, Guangdong, and
Sichuan provinces and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has over 100 stone quarries with estimated reserves of
several billion cubic meters. Its products have low radioactivity
and chromatism, and are lustrous, rigid, and resist wear.
</P>
<P>
The region has opened up 70 quarries that produce 60,000 cubic
meters of stone products in 47 varieties annually.
</P>
<P>
China exports 30 percent of its output to Japan, the Republic
of Korea, the Unites States, and Germany, and earns 780 million U.
S. dollars from it annually. It also spends 240 million U.S.
dollars on imports from Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 foreign companies and 2,700 collective and private
companies make up the bulk of stone producers. They have an annual
output value of 57 billion yuan on average.
</P>
<P>
Governments have adopted measures to encourage foreign firms to
invest in stone production. On average, producers can begin
showing a profit in a year and a half and processors can recover
their investment in 3 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Frowns on Human Skin Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye has said the government will mercilessly fight
the illegal trade of human skin.
</P>
<P>
Describing such a trade as "barbaric" and "shameful," Sumaye
called on the public to expose the culprits involved and do away
with superstitious beliefs, The Guardian reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Mbeya Region in southwest Tanzania said two
suspects have been seized in connection with the murder and
skinning of a 13-year-old boy for trade. In recent months, many
people have been found dead there with skin missing.
</P>
<P>
Some people superstitiously believe that human skin can protect
a house from evil spirits and agents of witch-craft, other people
believe that when associated with special rituals, human skins
increase harvests and even lure more customers to their clubs and
shops, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliament session in the central city of Dodoma
Monday, the prime minister called for immediate action against the
murderers, who are "a threat to the country's peace and
tranquility."
</P>
<P>
The paper said the government will seek assistance from Zambia
and Malawi, which borders Mbeya, to investigate the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
