<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China in Bid to Clean up 5th largest Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is gearing up an ambitious
program to clean up its fifth largest freshwater lake, Chaohu, in
east Anhui province, vice governor Zhang Ping has said.
</P>
<P>
All the 109 industrial firms in the lake areas must comply with
state pollution discharge standards by the end of this year. Those
that fail to do so will be shut down.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of China's efforts to tighten pollution
control over its major lakes and rivers, including Dianchi Lake in
Yunnan province and Haihe River in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
So far progress has been made to clean up the 13,000-km Chaohu,
since the Anhui provincial government launched the program last
October, with 27 enterprises having complied with the state-set
standards.
</P>
<P>
Chaohu and its surrounding areas are threatened by a yearly
discharge of 280 million tons of wastewater. It is also filling up
with more than two million tons of silt and mud annually that come
from the dwindling wetlands and banks around the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
