<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Citizens of Tianjin Still Work Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Over 90 percent of some 3,900
people above the age of 60 in the Chinese city of Tianjin still do
some kind of labor for the family, a recent survey has shown.
</P>
<P>
Of these aged between 60 to 80, 9.1 percent in the urban area
work at paid labor, 92.4 percent do some household chores, while
in rural areas 22.2 percent are still doing farmwork and 43.5
percent, household chores.
</P>
<P>
The reason that so few of these people have other jobs is bad
health, old age, or fear of being laughed at. Some think that
their pensions are sufficient, but some say they cannot find a
suitable job.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of those surveyed in rural areas say they
spend about three hours taking care of grand-children, buying
groceries, and cooking.
</P>
<P>
Professor Hao Maishou, who studies gerontology, says that
Chinese seniors have a tradition of proving themselves useful to
the family and society. He says that China is now becoming an
aging society with 120 million elderly, and this group of people
needs care from the society and more research is needed on the
subject. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
