<HEADLINE> Shanghai People's New Ideas About Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that more
people in Shanghai are spending their money on housing, medical
care, recreation, and education.
</P>
<P>
A survey on Shanghai consumer spending patterns showed an
average per capita spending on housing of 660 yuan (79 U.S.
dollars) and on medical care of 260 yuan last year, up 22 percent
and 32 percent respectively over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Average per capita spending on recreation and education went up
from 784 yuan in 1997 to 843 yuan last year, and on newspapers and
magazines it was 50 yuan and on cultural and recreational
activities, 72 yuan, up 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
With improvements in the standard of living and changing
consumer concepts, a car and computer and the Internet have become
the symbol of a modern and fashionable life for more Shanghai
citizens.
</P>
<P>
A survey by Beijing's Horizon Survey Company of 800 Shanghai
people above the age of 18 showed that a third of them put housing
first on their list of priorities for the next 2 years, while 15
percent putting buying a computer as their first priority and 13
percent, education.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that new high-tech durable goods, high quality
kitchenware, interior decoration, and tourism will become new
consumer items in Shanghai, and spending on education will
continue to go up proportionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
