<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW -- A Polish French-made TR-20 trainer plane Sunday
crashed near Rylina in the northern mountainous area of Slovakia,
injuring all the four pilots -- two Poles and two Slovaks -- on
board, with one Polish pilot in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The Polish News Agency reported that the accident occurred at
10:00 a.m. on Monday, but the Pilot Training Center of the Polish
Rzeszow Engineering Institute confirmed it only on Monday evening.
The first secretary in the Polish embassy in Slovakia said that
the cause of the accident remained unclear and a special
commission was sent to the spot for investigation. (Poland-Plane-
Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean Interior Minister Raul Troncoso confirmed
on Monday that President Eduardo Frei's cabinet has offered to
resign en masse, leaving its status at Frei's disposal.
</P>
<P>
Troncoso said that the president, who is considering a partial
reshuffle, has not decided whether or not to accept the
resignation. The ministers' resignation was aimed at seeking
solutions to social problems caused by economic crisis, drought
and slumping copper prices, according to government coordinator
Anselmo Sule. (Chile-Cabinet Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The out-going governor of Deutsche Bundesbank (German
central bank), Hans Tietmeyer, said on Monday that the euro still
has the potential of appreciation despite its recent weakness in
the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer told the press in Hannover, capital of Niedersachsen
State, pointed out that euro's recent devaluation against other
major currencies stemmed from a number of factors, including the
disparity of economic growth and interest rates between Europe and
the U.S. and the Kosovo crisis. Moreover, people had placed too
high hopes on the euro, he added. Ernst Welteke, who will succeed
Tietmeyer as the new governor of Deutsche Bundesbank on September
1, predicted that euro would rebound next year as U.S. economic
growth would begin to slow down then. (Germany-Bank-Euro) 
</P>
