<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Grotto Moved To Make Way For Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- a 1400-year-old grotto has been
moved to a museum to make way for the Xiaolangdi Hydro-electric
Power Project on the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
This is the most massive relocation of historical relics in
China and means moving 166 niches that house more than 200
Buddhist statues, 7 inscribed tablets, a 2-meter high Buddha, and
a mural.
</P>
<P>
The moving of the Xiwo Grotto in central China's Henan province
has taken archeologists and workers 4 years to complete the 7-step
move from the original site in Xin'an county to a county museum to
maintain its original look and to make way for the largest dam
project on the Yellow River. Xiaolangdi is intended to deal with
devastating floods of the kind that have plagued China for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Dam Project is 30 kilometers north of the city
of Luoyang in Henan Province. It will flood 32,300 hectares of
land and more than 176,000 people will have to move to higher
areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
