<HEADLINE> Cypriot Pilots On 24-Hour Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- About 70 percent of the pilots of
the national carrier Cyprus Airways (CY) pilots started a 24-hour
strike as of midnight Monday, with 11 flights to be grounded and
over 3,000 travelers to be affected.
</P>
<P>
The pilots' union PASIPY said the strike was triggered by the
management's failure to enforce a deal on freezing vacancies in
the airline's charter arm Eurocyprian until an agreement is
reached among all sides concerned on how to fill the posts.
</P>
<P>
Eurocypian pilots, CY management and PASIPY signed an agreement
in 1994 on promotions, which clearly states that promotions in the
charter firm should go to its pilots. But the parties concerned
agreed to hold a dialog on the issue in an accord reached last year.
</P>
<P>
But CY claimed the dialog collapsed on June 1 this year and
advertised two captain posts in CY and three in Eurocypria for
what it said urgent need to fill the vacancies.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, PASIPY announced it would go on strike against
the decision.
</P>
<P>
Eurocypria pilots were also threatening industrial action due
to the management's failure to fulfill the agreement and PASIPY
insisted the dialog be completed before the vacancies were
filled.
</P>
<P>
CY press spokesman Tasos Angeli said the strike will cost
thousands of pounds, and above all, it will have a bad effect on
Cyprus as a tourist destination and the company's image abroad.
</P>
<P>
The strike was also condemned by Communications and Works
Minister Leondios Ierodiaconou as "unjustifiable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
