<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Analysis: Asia Needs New Engine for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- When Asia's exports have run out of
steam, what could be the main source of the region's next phase of
growth?
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe that Asia should find other growth
engines when the region's exports are unlikely to grow at a fast
pace again in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
For over a decade, Asia's economic growth had to a large extent
relied on exports, which were described as one of the main
"engines" of the region's growth.
</P>
<P>
But now, when Asia's exports have become very weak, the region
may have to look for a new engine for a steady growth.
</P>
<P>
It is quite true that Asia's export-led growth strategy once
proved successful. "A number of successful economies have pursued
a development strategy of export-led growth, using policy to shift
their industrial structures toward exports and to exploit
economies of scale," said a recent Asian Development Bank report.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of such a strategy, Asia's export grew
at an annual rate of 20 to 30 percent in the 1980-1995 period. Due
to the high growth of exports, Asia became the fastest growing
region in the world in the past decade, and its economic miracle
won the admiration of other regions.
</P>
<P>
However, Asia's heavy reliance on exports had already shown
defects even before the regional financial crisis broke out in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, when the world electronics market experienced a
cyclical slowdown, Asia's export machine nearly broke down. As
electronics accounted for a large share of its exports, Asia's
export growth declined to 4.3 percent in that year from 20 percent
in 1994 and 22 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, Asia's economic growth slowed down from 8.2
percent in 1995 to 7.5 percent in 1996 and 6.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Asia's export growth has not recovered. Despite
large depreciation of Asian currencies in the financial crisis --
83 percent in Indonesia, 57 percent in South Korea, 55 percent in
Malaysia and 46 percent in Thailand -- Asian export growth
continued to be slow.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the regional economy grew only 4 percent as a result
of weak exports and the impact of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although exports in Asian countries like China, Singapore and
Thailand showed signs of recovery in May, gone are the days when
exports in the region could play its role as the main growth
source.
</P>
<P>
"That party is well and truly over," said Jim Walker, chief
economist at CLSA Global Emerging Markets, citing lower price and
profits worldwide and shrinking product cycles as a result of
fast-moving technology.
</P>
<P>
Some experts estimate that if Asian firms maintain their share
of the world market, the region's exports are expected to increase
by 5 to 10 percent in good years, and much less in bad years.
</P>
<P>
What could replace exports as the new engine of Asia's growth?
Many economists believe that Asia's vast domestic markets could
play the role if Asian economies could make a policy shift by
looking homeward.
</P>
<P>
"Asia needs a new source of growth. Luckily, such a source
exists and it's right here at home. There is a rich seam of
productivity gains waiting to be mined in Asia's domestic
economies," said the Far Eastern Economic Review in its recent
issue.
</P>
<P>
Since the third quarter of 1998, Asian countries have taken a
series of measures to stimulate the domestic demand. Governments
in the region have started infrastructure construction, increased
imports, lowered interest rates and urged higher consumption.
</P>
<P>
Such measures have already worked quite well. In the first
quarter of this year, South Korea's economy grew by 4.6 percent
from a severe recession last year, while Singapore and the
Philippines increased 1.2 percent. Production in Thailand and
Indonesia is also showing signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
The rebound in Asia is based on domestic economic improvements
rather than demand from overseas, said Stanley Fischer, first
deputy managing director of the International Monetary Fund in a
recent speech.
</P>
<P>
The signs of growth are coming from within, because "the export
markets for this region have been very weak," he said.
</P>
<P>
The improvements should encourage Asian economies to make a
policy shift by not overlooking the importance of domestic
markets, the new engine for the next phase of Asia's economic
growth, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 59,000 Detained in Combing Drive in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh's law-enforcing
agencies have arrested a total of 59,220 persons and recovered
more than 1,150 fire arms during their two months' country-wide
combing operation against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Malik Khasru, assistant inspector general of the Bangladeshi
police, disclosed this on Monday afternoon, the New Nation
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the arrested persons, 527 were listed terrorists, who
were directly involved in killing, raping, dacoity, mugging,
hijacking and extortion in different parts of the country,
especially in the southwestern region, according to Khasru.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the operation, peace has been restored to a
certain extent in the southwestern region, and people there have
gained their courage and confidence.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that to tackle the law and order situation in
the southwestern region, a continuous operation would be needed
with deployment of more force by setting up permanent camps in the
trouble-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
"A special drive is needed to deal with the long-standing
problems of terrorism, especially in the country's southwestern
regions," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
During the combing operation, the government has set up over
150 police camps at sensitive places, and members of the
paramilitary Bangladesh Rifles and Answers (village and border
militia) are actively participating in the operation which has
gained the support of the people, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The government launched the combing drive on April 21 following
bomb explosions early this year in two separate places in the
southwestern region that killed several political leaders and
activists and injured many others. The region has then reportedly
become a haven for terrorists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
