<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Snap Spurs' 12-Game Winning Streak with Game 3 Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The New York Knicks snapped the
NBA's longest single-season playoff winning streak as Allan
Houston tied a playoff career-high 34 points in an 89-81 triumph
over the San Antonio Spurs in Game Three of the Finals here
tonight.
</P>
<P>
The Spurs had won 12 straight games, including all six on the
road, before suffering their first loss since May 11 at home
against the Minnesota Timberwolves in the second game of their
Western Conference first-round series.
</P>
<P>
Houston made all 12 of his free throws and was 10-of-24 from
the field for the Knicks, who assured themselves the maximum three
home games for the lowest-seeded team in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
Game Four is on Wednesday and Game Five is Friday -- both at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
David Robinson led the Spurs with 25 points and Tim Duncan
added 20. Latrell Sprewell scored 24 points and Larry Johnson had
16 for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
After suffocating defense paced the Spurs to wins in each of
the first two games of the series, New York made adjustments
tonight and opened with 32 points in the first quarter to build an
11-point lead.
</P>
<P>
Despite totaling a combined 33 points in the next two quarters,
New York never relinquished the lead as the crowd, which included
NBA scoring champion Allen Iverson of the Philadelphia 76ers and
numerous celebrities, remained a factor throughout.
</P>
<P>
The good news for the Knicks was that they were able to win
without playing their best. They shot only 39.7 percent (31-of-78)
from the field but were even on the boards. The difference was
turnovers -- the Spurs commited 20, twice as many as New York.
</P>
<P>
San Antonio shot 44.6 percent (29-of-65) from the floor, as
Robinson and Duncan, San Antonio's "Twin Towers", combined to make
14-of-28. But the rest of the team was just 15-of-37 (40.5 percent)
and totaled only 36 points.
</P>
<P>
Duncan and Robinson paired up for 22 rebounds while Kurt Thomas
led the Knicks with 10. Marcus Camby, who started at center,
scored just five points before fouling out for New York.
</P>
<P>
Things look better now than they did for New York before Game
Three. Only two teams have won a championship after losing the
first two games, and no team has swept the middle three home games
since the 2-3-2 format was installed in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks has a chance to gain all the momentum on Wednesday
and thrust the pressure heavily on the favored Spurs, who entered
the NBA from the defunct ABA in 1976. San Anotonio never won an
ABA title and was stopped one round short of the NBA Finals four
times.
</P>
<P>
The Knicks, who last appeared in the NBA Finals in 1994, are
seeking their first title in 26 years. They became the first No. 8
seed to advance to the NBA Finals by beating the top-seeded Miami
Heat, Atlanta Hawks and the Pacers in the playoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
