<HEADLINE> Improper Zoo Facilities For Animals In Eastern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Animals at the city zoo in the
capital of China's Fujian Province are suffering from the same
problem as local people -- poor housing conditions and limited
living space.
</P>
<P>
When compared with the areas of zoos in other major Chinese
cities, the zoo at Fuzhou can only be called tiny, with its 4
hectares of land. It's only about one tenth of ordinary zoo areas
in other cities of the country.
</P>
<P>
And, even though the zoo has not been enlarged in recent years,
the number of animals kept growing, increasing to 130 types that
even include big animals like the elephant, orangutan, and tiger.
</P>
<P>
To provide them with more comfortable living conditions during
the hot summer, zoo keepers have to put some different animal
species together in the same house, like zebras and ponies, or
macaques and gibbons. And, to keep them from fighting over
territory while living in the same room, the keepers have to use
barriers to separate them into groups.
</P>
<P>
The severe housing problem for animals in the zoo has aroused
the attention of relevant departments. But whether the issue can
be properly settled in short time remains in doubt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Castle Opens To Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- An old castle in southwest China's
Guizhou Province that is believed to have been built during the
Middle Ages has had thousands of visitors this year.
</P>
<P>
Hailongtun Castle is on a 1.5-sq.km. mountainous part of
northern Guizhou and is surrounded by steep cliffs on three sides,
about 10 miles from the city of Zunyi.
</P>
<P>
The castle is believed to have been built during the late Tang
Dynasty (618-907) and served as an important fortress for a local
clan named Yang for 725 years.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou plans to spend 50 million yuan developing the castle
for a scenic spot. The first phase of construction has already
cost 6.8 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Sun Gang, deputy director of the State Tourism Administration,
was surprised during a visit to Guizhou and the castle last summer
to see that it is the most intact castle from that period in China.
</P>
<P>
Historical records report that the castle went into a period of
decline after the clan rebelled against the central government and
was attacked by military forces in retaliation about 400 years ago.
However, the walls, blockhouses, strategic passages, and dungeon
are almost completely intact. There are also palaces and buildings
for concubines that were built during the Song (960-1279) and Yuan
(1271-1368) dynasties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary Warns of Risks With Steel Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary William
Daley warned Monday that U.S. industries which rely heavily on
exports to other countries might suffer if the domestic steel
industry obtains quotas on foreign steel.
</P>
<P>
Daley issued the warning on the eve of a key vote in the Senate
on a quota measure. The House overwhelmingly passed the bill in
March, 289-141, despite the threat of a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
"It is not just the steel industry that stands to suffer. Other
industries that depend greatly on exports and could pay a steep
price include pharmaceuticals, high-tech, and above all,
agriculture," the Commerce Secretary said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. steelworkers are pushing for quotas as a way to combat low-
priced foreign shipments that the industry blames for bankruptcies
at three U.S. companies and for thousands of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Last year, foreign shipments reached record highs because of
the Asian economic turmoil, which reduced demand for steel abroad
and forced foreign producers turning to U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's news conference, Daley said steel quotas would
violate international trade agreements and make it difficult for
the U.S. government to persuade other countries to open their
markets to U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
The quota bill would impose monthly quotas on steel shipments
equal to the average levels in the three years before July 1997.
The measure also would set up an import notification system to
better track shipments into the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
