<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkokians Get More Health-Conscious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Residents in the Thai capital city
have become increasingly health-conscious and a majority of them
are interested in alternative medicine and new ideas to ensure
they live well, according to a survey by a leading advertising
firm, which is available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Listening Post, who conducted the survey early
this year, said that 82 percent of 203 people aged 19-40 said they
were concerned about their health.
</P>
<P>
Health issues were getting increased attention from local
marketers and advertisers, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Some 55 percent of respondents claimed to be interested in
learning or practicing new things beneficial to health.
</P>
<P>
Most of those who did put thought into action were aged 25-29,
with a bachelor's degree or higher education and from middle- and
upper-income households.
</P>
<P>
The changes in behavior were influenced by books, television
and radio, friends and doctors, with respondents citing a mix of
these factors, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the total surveyed claimed to have
heard of Thai traditional medicine and meditation techniques, with
as many as 20 percent understanding what was involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
