<HEADLINE> ADB Urges Nepal to Reduce Growing Dependence on Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank has
urged the Nepalese government to address the issue of growing
dependence on foreign aid but committed itself to continued strong
support for the country.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Director of the bank's Programs Department (Region
West) Geert van der Linden told the press that he briefed the
government on the increasing scarcity of the bank's concessional
loan funds and the need to utilize the aid more effectively and
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
He said the new majority government of Nepal understands well
that it should demonstrate its ability to use the assistance more
effectively.
</P>
<P>
Both the prime minister and finance minister made strong
assurances in this regard and agreed that frequent change of
project officials is very detrimental to the projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with senior government officials, Linden urged
the government to improve the revenue mobilization efforts through
effective implementation of the value-added tax and other
necessary tax reform measures to address the important issue of
growing dependence on foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
But he also assured the government of the bank's continued high
commitment to the development of Nepal, a press release issued by
the bank's Nepal Resident Mission said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the new majority government would
use its majority to address the many development challenges facing
Nepal so as to take the country back on the path of sustainable
growth and address poverty issues.
</P>
<P>
On the Melamchi water supply project which aims to improve
water supply in the Kathmandu Valley, the ADB official expressed
satisfaction that agreement had been reached between the Nepalese
government and the donor community on the implementation and
financing arrangements for the project.
</P>
<P>
He said it will take five to six years to complete the project
at a cost of 300 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
