<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fei Xiaotong, Harbinger Of China's Rural Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- He foresaw the development of
township businesses as a venue for China's rural reforms 50 years
ahead of time and soon drew up the next stage of the reforms,
which now seems feasible.
</P>
<P>
Fei Xiaotong, the Chinese anthropologist, is respected
worldwide for his lifetime of study and for his contribution to
China's rural economy. At the age of 89, he still devotes a third
of each year conducting investigation and research across the
country and seeing with his own eyes the changes reflecting his
second "prediction" about rural changes.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago he proposed that small market towns become a
powerful force in bridging the gap between town and country to
substantially improve the living standard of Chinese farmers and
stimulate the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
And, as it turned out, things are going just as he expected. By
the end of last year, there were 50,000 small towns across China
that had assimilated 100 million farmers and these township
communities have developed many primary planning functions modeled
after cities.
</P>
<P>
Fei's research was based on several decades of outdoor studies
and, in spite of a limp left from an accident in a mountainous
area, he was still able to cover all of China's provinces and
regions, with the exception of Tibet and Taiwan. He has been
honored as "the scholar who walked the longest journey in China,"
as he travels more than 30,000 km every year, almost as long as a
round-the-earth trip.
</P>
<P>
"A doctor's warning kept me from going to the highlands of
Tibet," he explains, and, "As for Taiwan, I will go there for
research as soon as it reunites with the motherland," Fei said in
his exclusively interview with Xinhua when he did investigation in
Changsha city.
</P>
<P>
He fell into a tiger pit while doing research with his wife
Wang Tonghui in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in 1935 and
hit a large boulder. His wife fell into a stream and drowned while
going to call for help.
</P>
<P>
Fei always says self-deprecatingly that he can no longer do any
skillful work, and can only do investigations and write articles.
</P>
<P>
Fei got his doctor degree at the London School of Economics
after studying with the prominent anthropologist Malinowski in
1938. His thesis on villages in China's Jiangsu Province, which is
his home, has been called the first anthropological research paper
in China.
</P>
<P>
He is esteemed by foreign colleagues as a voice for Chinese
farmers because of his incessant attempt to seek ways to help the
rural economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais Working Overseas Help Boost Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The money sent back home by Thais
working overseas will help the country recover from the economic
crisis, a report by Bank of Thailand's northeastern branch in Khon
Kaen province said.
</P>
<P>
The report, which is available Tuesday, said that 191,735
Thais, most of them from the Northeast, were working overseas last
year, an increase of 4.6 percent over the previous year. They
remitted 21.1 billion baht (570 million U.S. dollars) worth of
foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, monthly salaries offered by foreign
employers averaged between 15,000 and 18,000 baht (405-486
dollars) compared with around 39,000 baht (1,054 dollars) offered
by local employers for jobs of the same nature.
</P>
<P>
But fees charged by job-recruitment agencies ranged from
150,000 to 180,000 baht (4,050 to 4,860 dollars), which
discouraged Thai workers from seeking employment abroad, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the policies to solve the rising unemployment caused
by the economic crisis, the Labor Ministry has passed new rules
capping fees at 80,000 to 100,000 baht (2,162 to 2,702 dollars),
hoping more Thai workers will seek jobs overseas this year.
</P>
<P>
However, it is expected that the amount of money in baht term
remitted by Thai workers overseas this year would drop from last
year since the baht strengthened, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, more than two million people in Thailand become
jobless, making the country's unemployment rate surge to six
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Opens Up Insurance Market for Foreign Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has opened up its insurance
market to the outside by issuing last week wholly-owned foreign
insurers with licenses to operate in the country.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Planning and Investment (MPI) had issued
a life insurance permit to Canada's Manulife to run an insurance
company in Vietnam, according to a report of the latest issue of
Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
Under the license, the 8.5 million U.S. dollar insurance
company can offer corporate insurance, life insurance, reinsurance
and investment for a period of 50 years.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, MPI also granted a non-life insurance license
to a consortium that includes Allianz Aktienge-sellschaft of
Germany and AGF Asia Privated Ltd of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The 7.5 million dollar Allianz/AGF Insurance Company will offer
non-life insurance, reinsurance and capital investment as well as
other services for foreigners in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's non-life insurance has expanded rapidly -- growing 40
percent a year since 1994 -- mainly because of rising demand from
motorbike owners and, now, car drivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
