<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Spurred by the lowest mortgage interest and low
unemployment rates since the 1960s, national homeownership soared
in 1998 and probably will continue increasing for the next decade,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Monday by the Harvard University's Joint
Center for Housing Studies, found that about 1.8 million homes
have been built each year since 1996, and that the national
homeownership rate reached 66.3 percent last year. (US-Housing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Tanzania pledged Monday to continue servicing
the eight-billion-U.S. dollar external debts to sustain its
credibility to the donor community, a statement from the State
House said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that President Benjamin Mkapa will remain
committed to paying the external debts to ensure a reliable flow
of foreign aid. (Tanzania-Debts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa has never been in an economic
recession as was previously believed, Statistics South Africa said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Revised gross domestic product (GDP) figures for 1998 have
showed that the country's economy had grown by 0.2 percent in the
last quarter of 1998, and not by minus 0.3 percent as originally
reported.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the original figures, South Africa was technically
in a recession because it recorded negative growth rates for two
successive quarters. (SAfrica-GDP)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones industrial average moved lower Monday
on profit-taking from last week's gains.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed 39.58 lower at 10,815.98. The index gained 365.
05 points in the five straight sessions last week.
</P>
<P>
But the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 66.84 or
2.6 percent at 2,630.28. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 6.16
at 1,349.00. (US-Wall Street-Closing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The out-going governor of Deutsche Bundesbank (German
central bank), Hans Tietmeyer, said on Monday that the euro still
has the potential of appreciation despite its recent weakness in
the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer told the press in Hannover, capital of Niedersachsen
State, pointed out that euro's recent devaluation against other
major currencies stemmed from a number of factors, including the
disparity of economic growth and interest rates between Europe and
the U.S. and the Kosovo crisis. Moreover, people had placed too
high hopes on the euro, he added. (Germany-denounce censure
against euro) 
</P>
