<HEADLINE> ASEAN Senior Officials Meet in Myanmar on Transnational Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Senior Officials of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are meeting here to hold
preparatory discussions for the Second ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
on Transnational Crime which is to follow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Senior Officials Meeting, which began Monday,
discussed the 6th ASEAN Summit and Hanoi Action Plan, and areas of
cooperation among ASEAN members in transnational crime action
plan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting assessed and confirmed the minutes of the ASEAN
Senior Officials Meeting on Transnational Crime held in the
Philippines in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
Discussions were also held on the plans to be submitted to the
following Second ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on Transnational Crime.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting is expected to adopt an action plan of
extending ASEAN member countries' efforts to combat transnational
crime from the national and bilateral levels to the regional
dimension, and strengthen regional commitment and capacity to
undertake the expanded task.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN ministers are also expected to consider the
establishment of the ASEAN Center on Transnational Crime and
enhancing cooperation with dialogue partners and relevant
international organizations to effectively deal with transnational
crime in the region.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members countries have been fostering cooperation in
combating transnational crime for more than two decades. The
cooperation has expanded from dealing with the abuse of narcotics
and trafficking of illicit drugs to including terrorism, arms
smuggling, money laundering, illegal immigration and piracy.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN bodies, which are currently involved in formulating
policies and initiating activities against transnational crime,
are the ASEAN Chiefs of National Police, the ASEAN Senior
Officials on Drug Matters and the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on
Transnational Crime (AMMTC).
</P>
<P>
The First AMMTC was held in Manila, the Philippines on December
20, 1997 when the ministers adopted the ASEAN Declaration on
Transnational Crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
