<HEADLINE> Foreign Companies Hail Partnership in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Foreign companies in China spoke
highly of their joint ventures and partnership with Chinese
companies although many prefer wholly owned subsidiaries, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Experts and senior officials from major foreign companies in
China made their view clear on the collaboration and partnership
with Chinese firms at the 1999 Strategic Relationships Conference
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Henry Chow, chairman of IBM China Co Ltd, was quoted by China
Daily as saying joint ventures have their advantages if the two
partners smoothly collaborate and share their strong points.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely viable for a foreign company to enter the
Chinese market through launching a joint venture with a Chinese
partner," he said, adding that joint ventures will continue to be
established in China in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Khordoc, director of the International Development
of the conference board, said at yesterday's opening session of
the conference that strategic alliances and joint ventures
represent one of the most cost-effective means for companies to
access new markets, to grow and compete, without a significant
investment risk.
</P>
<P>
The conference also presented speeches by experienced
practitioners and consultants including JG Enterprises President
Julian Gresser, President of United Technologies Asian Operations
David Manke, and Sydney Chang, general manager of Armstrong World
Industries (China) Ltd.  
</P>
