<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Governors Confident in Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The out-going governor of Deutsche
Bundesbank (German central bank), Hans Tietmeyer, said on Monday
that the euro still has the potential of appreciation despite its
recent weakness in the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer told the press in Hannover, capital of Niedersachsen
State, pointed out that euro's recent devaluation against other
major currencies stemmed from a number of factors, including the
disparity of economic growth and interest rates between Europe and
the U.S. and the Kosovo crisis. Moreover, people had placed too
high hopes on the euro, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ernst Welteke, who will succeed Tietmeyer as the new governor
of Deutsche Bundesbank on September 1, said in Frankfurt that he
shared the same view with Tietmeyer, and predicted that euro would
rebound next year as U.S. economic growth would begin to slow down
then.
</P>
<P>
Recently, euro kept plummeting in trading with the U.S. dollar,
eroding people's confidence in the European currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
