<HEADLINE> Millennium in Hong Kong Exhibition Opens in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) opened an exhibition here on Monday in
a bid to further commercial and cultural ties between the Chinese
and Mexican peoples in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the exhibition, titled "Millennium in Hong Kong,
the Spirit of Dragon", Anson Chan, Administrative Secretary of
Hong Kong SAR, told the audience that Hong Kong would like to take
advantage of this opportunity to expand its various exchanges with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Trade relations between China and Mexico, which dated back to
the 16th century, should be further strengthened in the
forthcoming century through joint efforts, she said.
</P>
<P>
Chan, who kicked off her three-day official visit on Monday,
added that Hong Kong, which serves as a key gateway to the rest of
China for the world, wishes to promote itself in the Latin
American nation as an important tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the theme of the exhibition, she said that on China'
s lunar calendar, the next millennium would start with the Year of
Dragon, a figure which represents dynamism and strength of the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Quirono Ordaz, General Director of Operations for
Tourist Promotion, who attended the opening ceremony on behalf of
Secretary of Tourism, Silvia Hernandez Enriquez, said that the
event was of special significance as it will promote the Mexican-
Chinese ties and vitalize tourist exchanges between Mexico and
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, sponsored by the Tourist Association of Hong
Kong, is designed to help the Mexican people understand the
richness and variety of the culture of Hong Kong, which returned
to the motherland on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the two-month exhibition, there will be the presentation
of traditional ceremonies which take place throughout the year in
Hong Kong, including "The Marriage Ceremony", "The Tea Ceremony",
"The Chinese New Year or New Moon", "The Bun Festival" and "The
March of the Dragon".
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the traditional Chinese dances of the Dragon and the
Lion will also be performed in public places. 
</P>
