<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Medical Care In Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- When Liao Wenshan, from southern
China, was preparing for a visit to Tibet, his friends warned him
of the serious consequences of getting a cold in Tibet if no
treatment was available -- but Liao got the flu and recovered
quite soon and completed his scheduled visit.
</P>
<P>
Before 1959, Tibet, which covers a 1.2-million-square-kilometer
area, had only three official clinics that mainly helped the
Tibetan nobility, while serfs were too poor to see doctors and
could die of even the most minor of diseases because of a lack of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
After 40 years of development, however, there are 1,300 medical
institutions in Tibet employing 10,000 people. In 1994, the
central and regional governments spent 140 million yuan (16.9
million US dollars) building or renovating pharmaceutical plants
and medical training centers.
</P>
<P>
Li Chengsong, the director of the region's People's Hospital,
says that his hospital can do difficult operations and treat
plateau-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
This year, the regional government plans to allocate 220
million yuan, or 7 percent of the region's expenditures, for the
public health sector.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's population has increased to 2.44 million people from
one million in 1959, with Tibetans accounting for 95 percent of
that figure. The average life expectancy of Tibetans rose to 65
years, compared with 36 years in 1959, and there are 60 people who
are 100 years old or older in Tibet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0241 </DOCNO>
