<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Senate Approves Further Sale of Telstra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Senate approved
Monday night the sale of a further 16.6 percent of Telstra, the
national telecommunications carrier and the biggest company in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The first third of the state-run enterprise had been sold in
1987 and around 1.8 million Australians invested in it.
</P>
<P>
The second slice of the company will be sold within months and
the Howard government is expecting to raise about 10 billion U.S.
dollars to retire its debt which was up to 149 billion U.S.
dollars by last March.
</P>
<P>
The sell-off attracts vast attention in the society.
</P>
<P>
In the first sale, investors bought for 3.30 Australian dollars
a share and now Telstra shares are trading at 8.10 Australian
dollars a share, a gain of almost 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government appointed in advance a team to
prepare to float later this year but refused to reveal details
about how the second batch would be sold.
</P>
<P>
According to Australian Associated Press, the Senate voted 37
to 35 to pass the legislation as two key independents stood by the
government's side, and the support only came after the government
admitted defeat with its plan to sell all of Telstra by amending
its own legislation, limiting the total sale to no more than 49.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian oppositions including the Labor, the Democrats
and the Greens insistently opposed the bill arguing that it would
raise the unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
The Howard government is now hoping to rush through its goods
and services tax package this week because by July 1 the current
Senate will expire and the balance of power in the new one will
rest with the Australian Democrats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
