<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Sets IMF Exit Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- After over 30 years of
subservience, the Philippines finally hopes to cut the so-called
protective grip of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the
economy next year, Journal reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To make way for this plan, the Philippine government will rush
reforms in various facets of the economy to strengthen its
defenses against external shocks, the paper quoted Finance
Secretary Edgardo B. Espiritu as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was actually preparing for an exit program as
early as 1997 when the Asian financial crisis erupted, putting in
disarray most economies in the region.
</P>
<P>
As the impact of the crisis reverberated throughout the world,
the government opted to sign a precautionary arrangement with the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
The two year program, under which the Fund closely monitored
the country's economic performance with a set of criteria, will
end in March next year. It carries a total standby package of 1.4
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The targets pertain to the borrowing requirements of the public
sector, the level of foreign borrowings and net international
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government signed a new letter of intent with
the IMF last week committing continued reforms to ensure growth
not just this year but for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
The reforms include the revision of the Securities and Exchange
Act, the creation of bankruptcy courts, the rationalization of
fiscal incentives and the public sector reform program which would
include the local government units.
</P>
<P>
Once all of these reforms are in place, Manila can look forward
to the termination of IMF support programs which have dominated
Philippine finance over the last 37 years, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
