<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Begins Title Defense in European Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Reigning champions Yugoslavia
started to defend its title by beating Israel 81-61, while the
Czech Republic, Germany and Crotia all recorded their victories as
the European basketball championship began on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic stunned Lithuania 78-62, Germany upset
Greece 59-58 and Croatia edged Italy 70-68, all with surprises.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania, one of the favorites, was toppled by a team that
made its last appearance in 1991, even Arvydas Sabonis, who plays
for the Portland Trail Blazers, did not help Lithuania by
finishing with seven points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Forward Lubos Barton scored the most 24 points by making all
six of his 3-pointers, while Saulius Stombergas led Lithuania with
17 points.
</P>
<P>
However, other NBA stars had their sparkling evening. Toni
Kukoc of the Chicago Bulls, with 16 points, paced a Croatian
comeback from a 19-point halftime deficit against Italy, runner-up
two years ago, while Dirk Nowitzky, the Dallas Mavericks rookie,
scored 21 points as Germany shocked Greece.
</P>
<P>
Russia crushed Slovenia 68-47 and Turkey beat Bosnia-
Herzegovina 57-42, behind 14 points from Hidayet Turkouglu.
</P>
<P>
Spain, expected to be another medal contender, came from behind
to beat Hungary 84-75, while France struggled to edge Macedonia 71-
67 behind Tariq Abdul-Wahad, the Sacramento Kings forward, who led
France with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
Dejan Tomasevic paced Yugoslavia with 24 points and 12 rebounds
in its opening Group A game in Toulouse, as Tomasevic and Dejan
Bodiroga keyed a 14-0 run that put Yugoslavia firmly in control.
</P>
