<HEADLINE> More United Customers Use E-Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 21 (Xinhua) -- United Airlines, the largest
airline in the world, reported Monday that last month more of its
customers used electronic tickets than paper tickets for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
May ticketing revealed that 51 percent of the more than 7
million tickets used on the airline worldwide were electronic ones.
</P>
<P>
The United Airlines launched electronic ticketing in 1994 and
now it is available to 95 percent of the destinations the airline
served worldwide.
</P>
<P>
In a survey conducted by the company, more than 70 percent of
its customers using electronic ticketing said they prefer it to
other ticketing options for the convenience and hassle-free travel
it provides.
</P>
<P>
Domestic customers using electronic tickets are not required to
carry anything other than identification and, in some instances,
the credit card used to pay for the ticket.
</P>
<P>
International customers are requested to carry their ticket
receipt. Unlike paper tickets, with electronic tickets, there is
no need to worry about ticket pick-up or delivery. An electronic
ticket can be issued instantly over the telephone or through the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, customers don't have to worry about losing tickets.
Losing a paper ticket can involve purchasing a new one and paying
a lost ticket fee of 75 U.S. dollars. Besides, with an electronic
ticket, changes to an itinerary can easily be done over the
telephone, saving an extra trip to have a ticket re-issued or
updated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
