<HEADLINE> More Highways Protected by Trees in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Trees have been planted along more
than 10,000 kilometers of highways in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, a dry place with deserts in northwest China, accounting
for one third of its total highway mileage.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have been made to curb the damage of highways
caused by drought, scarce vegetation, sand and floods and ensure
the safety of transport, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
The region has 32,000 kilometers of highways, but 17,000
kilometers of them run through Gobi and cold uplands, making it
hard to plant trees.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, however, set aside a lot of funds annually in recent
years to along highways where trees are viable.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the region built gardens, fruit yards, vegetable
yards and grape trellises along its highways.  
</P>
