<HEADLINE> Kasparov Challenges the World in Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Chess world champion Garry
Kasparov moved a queen's pawn here on Monday to start his Internet
chess match against the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The challenge, organized by Microsoft, was initiated as
Kasparov, who was defeated two years ago by Big Blue computer,
moved his white pawn to e4 on a giant chessboard in a New York
City park.
</P>
<P>
"I invite people from all over the world to play with me in the
ultimate chess match on MSN.COM," he said, adding "where else but
on the Internet can you play the world champion?"
</P>
<P>
Both Kasparov and the world have 24 hours to make each of their
move as players from all over the globe log on and vote to
determine the black pieces' strategy.
</P>
<P>
Etienne Bacrot, 16, of France, Florin Felecan, 19, of the
United States, US player Irina Krush, 15 and German Elisabeth
Pahtz, 14, will serve as experts for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov said "I hope I'm a favorite in this game and the whole
game would last 3-40 moves and would be over by late August or
early September." 
</P>
