<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of today'
s major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin has called for unremitting
efforts to control Yellow River flooding, better use its water
resources and create a good ecological environment along its
course.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made his remarks yesterday in the capital of central
Henan Province and explained, "This has always been a major task
for the Chinese nation and is of great strategic significance for
sustained socio-economic development along the river and
nationwide."
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of China's National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, met here yesterday with Cambodian National
Assembly President Norodom Ranarith.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that, under the leadership of King Norodom Sihanouk,
Cambodia has smoothly realized ethnic reconciliation. China is
happy to see that, following the formation of the new National
Assembly and government, the two major parties, out of concern for
the overall interests of the country and the nation, have engaged
in cooperation, and made new progress in both domestic and foreign
affairs, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Nawaz Sharif, prime minister of Pakistan, will pay a working
visit to China as of June 28 at the invitation of Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue announced
here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- The remains of Chen Xilian, a former vice-premier of China,
who died June 10 at the age of 85, were cremated here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the NPC, Vice-
Premier Li Lanqing and other Chinese leaders attended a mourning
ceremony for Chen at Babaoshan Revolutionary Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A senior Chinese lawmaker said here today that there exists
enormous potential for Sino-Russian border economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Zou Jiahua, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, made
the remark at a Sino-Russian seminar on regional cooperation
oriented toward the 21st century, which opened in Beijing
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese scientists announced yesterday that they have
successfully developed an embryo of a giant panda using clone
technology, which could be a critical and exciting breakthrough
for saving an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences explained that
they had introduced the cells of a dead female panda into the egg
cells of a Japanese white rabbit. They then spent 10 months
carefully nurturing the embryo, which was a year ahead of
expectations.  
</P>
