<HEADLINE> World Tourism Industry Earnings to Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The world tourism industry is
expected to double its revenue in the next 20 years, predicted
former president of the World-wide Hotel and Restaurant
Association (WWHRA) Eric Pfeffer on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local newspaper "El Pais," Pfeffer
said that at least one in ten people in the world are now involved
directly or indirectly in the tourism.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the world-wide tourism industry accounted for almost
10 percent of the total world Gross Domestic Product (GDP),
earning 600 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, revenue from business travels represented 50 percent
of the total tourism earnings, while in some developed countries,
such as the United States, the figure reached 70 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
Pfeffer was the WWHRA president in 1998, and now is the
Executive President of the hotel division, Cendant, a consortium
of eight hotel chains grouping a total of 6,200 hotels in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
