<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Police Advisers Arrive in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The first contingent of
international police advisers, unarmed and wearing blue U.N. caps,
arrived in the East Timor capital of Dili on Monday to assist in
the August direct ballot in the territory, according to reports
reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 41 police officers who arrived on Monday, the first of some
270 civilian police advisers, were drawn from Australia, Ireland,
New Zealand, Spain and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The police officers would be limited to an advisory role, and
they will act in an advisory capacity to the Indonesian police,
who are responsible for ensuring East Timor remains peaceful in
the run-up to the vote.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman in East Timor David Wimhurst said Indonesian
police would be ultimately responsible for maintaining law and
order.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., which is organizing the ballot, hopes the officers
will be able to stem a tide of violence convulsing East Timor
ahead of the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
Wimhurst also disclosed that the U.N. mission has opened voter
registration centers in Dili, Baucau, Suai and Same. Later this
week it plans to open similar centers in Viqueque, Los Palos,
Ermera and Maliana regencies.
</P>
<P>
U.N. special representative on East Timor Jamsheed Marker is on
his way to East Timor. Marker held talks with President B.J.
Habibie, Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas and other senior
Indonesian government officials in Jakarta on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Marker said he was encouraged by ongoing preparations for the
direct ballot to be held in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say whether the U.N. would go ahead with its
original plan to hold the self-determination vote on August 8 or
postpone it because of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Since January, dozens of East Timorese have been killed in
clashes between the warring factions.
</P>
<P>
"I think the process is going well and we hope this will
continue. The U.N. will continue with all it can to bring about
this peaceful solution," Marker said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas acknowledged there were still minor incidents in East
Timor, but said the government would be able to ensure an
atmosphere conducive to the ballot process.
</P>
<P>
He said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan would make his final
decision on the ballot date after receiving Marker's report on the
East Timor situation.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5,
the U.N. will deploy civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police in maintaining law and
order. A key function will be the disarmament of rival factions
that are either for or against independence.
</P>
<P>
The August 8 ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent. The Indonesia government has
announced that it would grant East Timor independence if the
people in the territory reject Indonesia's offer of a
wide-ranging autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' 91-day T-bill Drops to 46-month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' benchmark 91-day
treasury bill (T-bill) rate dropped Monday to a 46-month low of
9.067 percent, the lowest recorded since August 8, 1995 when the
yield settled at 8.932 percent, a local newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National Treasurer Leonor Briones was quoted by the Philippine
Star as saying that the drop was widely anticipated due to the
continued easing of the inflation rate coupled with the Central
Bank's decision to reduce its key overnight rates anew last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Investors swarmed the auction floor Monday with total tenders
reaching a four-month high of 16.377 billion pesos (409 million
U.S. dollars), an indication of a very liquid financial market,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Rates for the 182-day T-bills declined to 9.355 percent from
the previous week's 9.679 percent while yields for the 360-day
T-bills eased to 10.262 percent from 10.625 percent a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo B. Espiritu said earlier that the
rates for the bellwether 91-day T-bills may drop to as low as 8.7
percent following the continued easing in inflation rate and the
Central Bank's key overnight rates.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate slowed down to 6.7 percent in May from eight
percent in April while the Central Bank effected Monday another
25-point reduction in its key overnight rates, the 18th time this
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Department of Finance inked Monday the agreement
for the government's small denominated treasury bonds aimed at
mobilizing savings and enhance further development of the
country's capital markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
