<HEADLINE> Anhui Starts Work on New Expressway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province has
started to construct its section of an expressway linking
Huangshan City with Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The expressway is to be built at a cost of 1.6 billion yuan,
and is expected to open for traffic in the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, the driving time between the two cities will
be halved to two hours.
</P>
<P>
During the past two decades, the Mount Huangshan tourism area
has received a combined total of 20 million domestic and overseas
visitors and earned more than 1.3 billion yuan from tourism, with
the earnings showing a 35 percent annual growth.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of tourists in the province visit the Mount
Huangshan scenic area, which attracts more visitors than any other
tourism destination in China.
</P>
<P>
Mount Huangshan has been entered on UNESCO's World Heritage
List of cultural and natural sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Language Tests Set New Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Additional standards for testing
the abilities of Chinese foreign-language learners are expected to
be established by the Nation Educational Examinations Authority (
NEEA) of the Ministry of Education, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
NEEA will try the "public English test systems" (PETs) program
in September in Beijing and Tianjin and in Guangdong, Liaoning and
Shandong provinces before expanding it into other regions next
year, said its director Yang Xuewei.
</P>
<P>
With implementation of the PETs program for English, the NEEA
expects to set up Russian and Japanese test systems in the near
future, said Yang.
</P>
<P>
PETs, jointly designed by the center and the British University
of Cambridge Local Examinations Syndicate (UCLES), aims to
evaluate, in a scientific way, students' mastery of English
listening, speaking, reading and writing skills, according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
Deadlines for participants to apply for PETs are March 31 and
September 15.
</P>
<P>
PETs places no limits on an applicant's age, gender, job,
educational background or to the regions where they work or live,
according to the center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
