<HEADLINE> Italy Names New Minister to Accelerate Institutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Antonio Maccanico was appointed
Monday to the Reform Minister by Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema to push along long-awaited changes in the country's
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"I believe he is extraordinarily suited to this job," said
D'Alema Monday, commenting on the new Minister for Institutional
Reforms, whose task is to draft changes to Italy's electoral
system and its form of government.
</P>
<P>
"Institutional reforms remain one of the priorities of this
legislature," D'Alema said, adding that "the government must push
reforms along with intelligence and maintaining dialogue with all
political forces."
</P>
<P>
Maccanico, aged 75, is a renowned mediator and deal-maker from
the center ground of politics. This reputation was one of the
reasons he was called on in 1996 to forge a coalition government
which would have ushered in reforms, including that of the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
He failed by a whisker to knit a coalition together and instead
had to settle for the job of posts and telecommunications minister
in the government of Romano Prodi which emerged from subsequent
elections.
</P>
<P>
Since losing his job when D'Alema formed a new government last
autumn, Maccanico has been chairman of the Senate's commission on
constitutional affairs - a key talking shop on reform.
</P>
<P>
Between 1988 and 1991 he was regional affairs minister in two
successive Christian Democrat governments.
</P>
<P>
Recently he joined the Democrats party, a formation founded by
Romano Prodi to carry on the ideals of the center-left Olive Tree
government he led for two and a half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
