<HEADLINE> British MPs Wants to Probe Secret Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A committee of British members of
parliament pressed the government on Monday to allow them greater
freedom to probe the activities of the security and intelligence
agencies, better known as MI5 and MI6.
</P>
<P>
A report by the House of Commons home affairs committee said
current arrangements for supervision of the agencies should be
replaced by a fully independent parliamentary committee with wider
powers, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994 the agencies, previously secret and beyond the
scrutiny of parliament, have been subject to a watchdog committee
of MPs appointed by the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"We conclude that the present statutory arrangements for
oversight of the intelligence and security agencies by the
Intelligence and Security Committee should be replaced by a
parliamentary select committee or committees," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The key feature must be that the scrutiny committee should be
more clearly seen to be independent of the executive," the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament say that despite the 1994 reform, their
ability to monitor the two agencies, which handle foreign
intelligence and domestic counter-espionage, is very limited
compared with counterparts in other countries, according to
Reuters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
