<HEADLINE> Sampras, Graf Advance in Wimbledon Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Men's top seed Pete Sampras of the
United States had a smooth start on the way to defend his
Wimbledon title by beating Australian Scott Draper 6-3, 6-4, 6-4
in the first round on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The American world number one is bidding to become the only man
of the century to win the singles title six times and he was in
inspired form as he cruelly exposed the gulf of ability between
himself and his 63rd-ranked opponent.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, winner in 93, 94, 95, 97 and 98, met little challenge
from the Australian in centre court, which drew a capacity of
crowd to enjoy the match.
</P>
<P>
"You can get the jitters in your first match out there but as
soon as I got on the court I felt right at home.
</P>
<P>
"For an opening match I couldn't have asked for anything better
-- I am motivated to do well here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was joined in the second round by Britain's Tim Henman,
the sixth seed, who beat Arnaud di Pasquale 6-4, 6-0, 3-6, 7-6 (7-
1) and 13th-seeded Slovak Karol Kucera who destroyed Mexican
Alejandro Hernandez 6-2, 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Australian Mark Philippoussis was the first men's singles seed
to go through when his booming serve demolished Belgian teenager
Xavier Malisse 6-7, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
In the women's draw, second seed Steffi Graf breezed past Czech
Ludmila Cerranova 6-1, 6-4 while fourth seed Monica Seles made
light work of Spain's Cristina Torrens-Valero 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Seven-times champion Graf looked completely at home back on
grass after her French Open victory and said: "I feel good... I
feel in good shape and I've trained well and prepared well.
</P>
<P>
"I'm ready for the next round and nothing else right now."
</P>
<P>
American Seles made the most of her double-fisted, disguised
groundstrokes to wrongfoot her Spanish opponent as she romped to
victory.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Amanda Coetzer, seeded 12, eased past Australian
Nicole Pratt 6-2, 7-5 but Anna Kournikova had a tough start
against Austrian wild card Barbara Schwartz before winning 7-6 (7-
2), 4-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova was named 17th seed when the number 10, American
Serena Williams, pulled out with influenza.
</P>
<P>
Serena's sister, sixth-seeded Venus, maintained the Williams
family challenge by beating Miriam Oremans of the Netherlands 6-1,
7-5.
</P>
<P>
Two matches were suspended on the first day due to bad light.
The men's singles first round match between Sweden's Magnus
Larsson and Russia's Yevgeny Kafelnikov, ranked third, was stopped
with the score (Larsson first) 7-6 (7-4), 5-7, 6-7 (6-8).
</P>
<P>
The women's singles match between Jennifer Capriati and Anke
Huber also had a halt with the score level at one set each and 5-5.
</P>
<P>
German Huber had taken the first set 7-5, with American
Capriati hitting back to win the second 6-3. The resumption will
be the second match on center court on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
