<HEADLINE> UK's Blair to Refocus on Domestic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
will use a major policy speech on Tuesday to refocus his party's
sights on the domestic agenda, after the Labor Party's disastrous
performance in the recent elections for Members of European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Blair will travel to the midlands city of Birmingham to
highlight the success of his government's New Deal job creation
scheme, billing it as the epitome of New Labour in action, his
official spokesman was quoted as saying by Reuters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a classic example...of New Labour enterprise made
real," Blair will say, celebrating the 100,000th young unemployed
person to get a job through the New Deal subsidy scheme since
Labour took power in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will reject accusations Labour has neglected
its traditional working-class supporters in its relentless pursuit
of middle class votes, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
"We will serve people of all ages and background, even those
who didn't vote for us," he will say.
</P>
<P>
John Monks, head of trade union umbrella body the TUC and
widely seen as a New Labour loyalist, said on Saturday that Blair
treated long-time Labour voters like "embarrassing elderly
relatives", shunning them in his drive for modernisation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, John Edmonds, chief of the GMB union, warned Labour
that unless it switched its focus to party loyalists it risked
them staying at home in the next general election, due by 2002, as
they did in droves in the European poll two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman said the suggestion that Labour achievements
such as lower taxes, cuts in unemployment and hefty increases in
child benefit were only of interest to well-off pockets of the
population was "ludicrous".
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that while the opposition Conservative
Party's hostility to adopting the euro currency had yielded
short-term gains, in the long term they would be marginalised as a
one-issue party.
</P>
<P>
"It will become clearer and clearer they have nothing to say on
jobs, schools and crime," he was quoted saying.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman also angrily denied media reports that the
Prime Minister had gone cool on the euro in the face of hostile
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
Party sources said Blair would address Labour MPs on Wednesday
to review what lessons could be learned from the European poll,
which gave opposition Conservatives more seats than Labour in
Brussels, Reuters said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
