<HEADLINE> US, Cuba Hold Talks on Counter-narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Four U.S. officials met Monday
in Havana with Cuban officials to discuss ways of improving
counter-narcotics cooperation but that does not indicate a change
of U.S. policy towards Cuba, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
Michael Ranneberger, who heads the State Department's office of
Cuban affairs, said the meeting was taking place within guidelines
for law enforcement efforts on counter-narcotics, the Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team consisted of two State Department and two Coast
Guard officials, none of whom holds a high rank. They were to
spend only one day in Cuba, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Only a small portion of the drugs entering the United States
come through Cuba, McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the island's location and a growing
tourist market could make it an opportune target for drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Cuba lacks the resources to counter large drug-trafficking
organizations, so drugs are routinely flown over Cuba or dumped in
Cuban waters without effective resistance by local authorities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the talks did not mean a change of
policy towards Cuba. The U.S. administration maintained an
embargo against the country attempting to topple the current Cuban
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
