<HEADLINE> Clinton Phones Blair on the Deaths of British Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) - The United States President Bill
Clinton on Monday phoned British Prime Minister Tony Blair to
express condolences over the deaths of two British soldiers in an
explosion in Kosovo, Blair's office said.
</P>
<P>
The two soldiers were killed on Monday after a blast involving
what might have been the remains of NATO bombs in Kosovo. Their
deaths were the first NATO fatalities since the military alliance
deployed its peacekeeping force in Kosovo 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is currently visiting the Balkans, "phoned to
express his condolences to the prime minister", Blair's spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were killed while removing munitions from a school
in the village of Negrovce, some 30 km (20 miles) west of the
Kosovo capital Pristina, a British army statement said earlier.
</P>
<P>
A BBC report quoted witnesses as saying that 50 explosives were
being collected by British bomb experts when the blast happened.
</P>
<P>
At least two civilians were also killed in the blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
