<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Names Civilian Administrator and Refugee Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A French Government
official will take charge of administering Kosovo and a New
Zealand refugee expert will oversee the return and resettlement of
those who fled the Serbian province, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dominique Vian, currently the prefect or governor of French
Guayana, will be Annan's deputy special representative for the
interim civilian administration of Kosovo -- overseeing everything
from the police to schools, buses and electric plants.
</P>
<P>
Dennis McNamara, currently the special envoy of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees for former Yugoslavia, will be the
secretary-general's deputy special representative in charge of
refugee return and humanitarian assistance, U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard announced.
</P>
<P>
Under a proposed plan for Kosovo, which Annan unveiled a week
ago, the U.N. peace mission, the United Nations Interim
Administration Mission (UNMIK), will have four deputies serving
under a special representative. The plan has to win endorsement
from the 15-nation Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, who is currently on an official visit to
Russia, has not yet made a decision on a special representative to
oversee the challenging civilian operation aimed at taking Kosovo
and its people and its people from the devastation of war to an
economically secure future without fear of renewed ethnic
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
In answering to a press question, Eckhard said that the future
U.N. special representative for Kosovo will be a European
national. Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, assumed his responsibility as the special
representative on interim basis since he arrived in Pristina,
provincial capital of Kosovo, on June 13.
</P>
<P>
Annan said last Saturday in Paris on his way to Moscow that the
special representative would be a European. That ruled out the
leading American candidate, Jacques Klein, a deputy to the
international community's top Bosnian envoy, Carlos Westendrop.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general has put the European Union in charge of
reconstruction and has given the 54-nation Organization for
Security and Cooperation in European primary responsibility for
rebuilding government institutions and organizing election.
</P>
<P>
Vian, 54, a lawyer, has been prefect for French Guyana since
February 1997, in charge of 51 local administrations, 6,500 civil
servants and regional cooperation with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
McNamara has held a variety of posts at the UNHCR, most
recently as director of international protection for the agency's
staff. He also ran the human rights component of the U.N.
peacekeeping operation in Cambodia ahead of 1993 elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
