<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP, Habitat Welcome G-8 Cologne Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Executive Director of the United
Nations Environment Program (UNEP), Klaus Toepfer, Monday welcomed
the debt relief plan agreed to by world leaders at the G-8 Summit
in Cologne, Germany, last weekend.
</P>
<P>
"Debt relief is a necessary precondition for sustainable
development - an important step toward increasing resources for
education, health and the environment," Toepfer told the press in
Kenyan capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Toepfer, who is also acting director of the United Nations
Center for Human Settlements, added that debt relief is also
essential in order to alleviate the conditions of the urban poor.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Cologne Debt Initiative and the re-launch of the High
Indebted Poor Countries initiative, is a clear signal that debt
relief and overseas development assistance must increasingly be
tied to good governance, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Debt relief will alleviate the living conditions of the billion
people who are homeless or live without adequate shelter in the
cities, only when governments and local authorities commit
themselves to better urban governance, he said.
</P>
<P>
World leaders at the G-8 Summit agreed in Cologne last weekend
to the 1999 Cologne Debt Initiative, which is expected to write
off debts of 36 countries totaling 70 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
