<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Urged to Approve Ministerial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Nigerian government
official Monday urged the Senate to timely approve the list of the
ministerial nominees submitted by President Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
Only five of the 49 nominees were cleared last week by the
109-member Senate, two weeks after the list was submitted to the
upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing held in Nigerian capital Abuja Monday,
Doyin Okupe, special assistant to the president on media and
publicity, said that "the delay in the clearance of the nominees
has created international anxiety."
</P>
<P>
He urged the senators, who have constitutional responsibility
for approving ministerial nominees, to "have a quick and
dispassionate look at the list", warning that further delay could
"cripple the government."
</P>
<P>
The list has generated much controversy but most Nigerians
argue that it should be approved to enable the president to get on
with the business of addressing the country's daunting problems.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo met with the senators five days ago in an
effort to drum up support for his nominees.
</P>
<P>
The Senate last week asked the president to provide additional
information on the other nominees, some of whom have been
criticized as "being a return of discredited former public
servants."
</P>
<P>
Okupe said that "a lot of communication had gone on between the
Senate and the president in the last few days" in an effort to
resolve areas of disagreement and ensure timely clearance.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, the Senate has been flooded with
avalanche of petitions by different interest groups over the
nomination of certain persons for ministerial appointment.
</P>
<P>
Senator Arthur Nzeribe confirmed having received more than 100
petitions against most of the nominees.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four out of the 49 ministerial nominees will appear
before the Senate Tuesday with more information about themselves.
</P>
<P>
The nominees are expected to show proof of having paid their
taxes consecutively in the past three years and to provide
evidence of their medical report to show that they are fit persons
to be appointed as ministers.
</P>
<P>
Other hurdles which must be scaled by each of the ministerial
nominees include possession of voter's registration card, written
evidence of declaration of assets and membership card of his or
her political party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
