<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's GDP Figures Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has never been
in an economic recession as was previously believed, Statistics
South Africa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Revised gross domestic product (GDP) figures for 1998 have
showed that the country's economy had grown by 0.2 percent in the
last quarter of 1998, and not by minus 0.3 percent as originally
reported.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the original figures, South Africa was technically
in a recession because it recorded negative growth rates for two
successive quarters.
</P>
<P>
The revisions followed Statistics South Africa's use of the
United Nations-prescribed System of National Accounts 1993 (1993
SNA), in calculating the country's quarterly real growth rates and
the revised annual real growth rates.
</P>
<P>
The new method pushes GDP level upward by a few percent through
 counting certain activities into GDP for the first time, the
organization said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's annual growth in real GDP over the
five-year period from 1993 to 1998 has been boosted from the
original 2.2 percent to 2.7 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
By applying the new method, Statistics South Africa had
identified new economic activities, noticeably in the
communications sector, including the rapid spread of cellular
phones, Internet-use and satellite TV.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that since the economy opened up to the
pressures of globalization following the 1994 election, there had
been notable increases in existing economic activity, such as the
taxi industry, private health services, and financial and
government services.
</P>
<P>
The increase in real GDP for the first quarter of this year was
 calculated at 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The best news about the figures was they showed that the
country was technically never in a recession, said Maria Ramos,
Director-General of the South African Finance Department.
</P>
<P>
"I think what these numbers mean, is that the economy is more
buoyant, more resilient, and the potential for future growth is
greater than we anticipated," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates indicated that the 1998/99 deficit, set
at 3.3 percent in April this year, would probably be coming in at
somewhere in the area of 2.9 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
Other growth numbers are also expected to be revised upward for
the next few years, including the debt to GDP ratio and the tax to
GDP ratio.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the figures should boost South Africa's image among
credit rating agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
