<HEADLINE> "Policy Has Not Changed One Iota" Towards Euro, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) - There would be no change in the
Britain's policy towards the EU's single currency, an official
spokesman from the Prime Minister's office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also denied there had been any shift in the tone
of policy in recent weeks, saying "policy has not chanted one
iota. The tone has not changed."
</P>
<P>
However, Tony Blair said on Sunday it would be "daft" for
Britain to join the single currency straight away and insisted
that there would have to be further economic reform in Europe
before Britain could sign up.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Radio 4, the Prime Minister acknowledged that the
public had "real concerns" about Europe and admitted that the
Tories had received a short-term boost from the Euro-sceptic vote.
</P>
<P>
In the European elections on June 13, Tony Blair saw his
party's share of the vote collapse from its high water mark of 44
percent at the General Election in 1997 to 28 percent, while the
Conservatives were up from 32 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman refused to confirm whether or not the prime
minister would attend a conference next month to support Britain's
membership of the euro.
</P>
<P>
The matter was dependent on other potential priorities in
Blair's agenda, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the comments are bound to fuel
speculation at Westminster that the Govenment's timetable for a
referendum on British entry to the single currency is slipping.
</P>
