<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wearable Computing A Potential Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Researchers have been finding
ways to make PCs really "personal", worn by people much as
eyeglasses or clothing.
</P>
<P>
Now the wearable computer market is evolving from a research
and development focused, start-up environment to a product- and
customer-oriented market. According to a report released Monday by
market analysis firm International Data Corporation (IDC), the
market in the United States will reach 600 million U.S. dollars by
2003.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the U.S. wearable PC marketplace will be driven by
the demand in the industrial, manufacturing, military, government
and medical sectors. "Wearable computing will start to play a key
role in cost cutting and increasing productivity for many
industrial users in the next five to ten years," IDC said. "The
true mobility of wearable computing will expand PC opportunities
to markets and job functions PCs have not been able to penetrate
up until now."
</P>
<P>
The potential market opportunities have attracted the efforts
of many companies and universities in the United States. IBM's
Almaden Research Center, for instance, has been working on a
number of variations of the wearable PC, such as a "belt" computer
that let users surf, dictate and edit documents while they are
moving around. It is also working on personal area network (PAN)
technology, which uses the natural electrical conductivity of the
human body to transmit electronic data. In the future, a user of
PAN technology will be able to transfer information via touch
rather than issuing typed commands or pressing buttons.
</P>
<P>
Vehicle maintenance users, particularly large vehicles such as
aircrafts, will find that a wearable computer can cut down on the
need to refer to paper-based manuals and increase accuracy on the
job. Medical workers will have immediate access to records,
reference materials, and with communications capabilities, other
medical resources.
</P>
<P>
But wearable computing may be a commercial application only for
the next few years. According to IDC, the biggest challenge to the
wearable computing industry is user education. Although many
useful applications will be developed, the majority of end users
will remain confused about the form factor.
</P>
<P>
IBM researchers stress the value of the functionality as well
as the social context, saying that the technology has to be
purposeful and relevant to the situation, or people won't bother
wearing it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
