<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders 300 Planes Home after Yugoslav Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
authorized the return of more than 300 of the U.S. aircraft which
participated in the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia to their home
bases.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen said NATO Supreme Commander
Gen. Wesley Clark would decide on details of the redeployment.
However, Cohen added that the first planes, as well as some
reserves called up for the campaign, could start returning as
early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first wave of returning aircraft will include B-1 and B-52
bombers and F-117 stealth fighters
</P>
<P>
The secretary, who returned Sunday from a tour of the region,
told a Pentagon news conference that the crews of the planes
"helped to make airpower history."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that 47,000 Serb troops have left Kosovo in the past
11 days, taking with them 800 tanks, armored personnel carriers
and artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
"NATO is well on its way toward meeting its goals of getting
the Serb forces out, getting NATO peacekeepers in and getting the
refugees back home," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
However, Cohen admitted that the peace-keeping operation ahead
is still very difficult. "Hatred does not heal quickly...Our
troops and the people of Kosovo still face a very daunting task in
the months ahead." 
</P>
