<HEADLINE> U.S. Homeownership Rate Hits 66.3 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Spurred by the lowest mortgage
interest and low unemployment rates since the 1960s, national
homeownership soared in 1998 and probably will continue increasing
for the next decade, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Monday by the Harvard University's Joint
Center for Housing Studies, found that about 1.8 million homes
have been built each year since 1996, and that the national
homeownership rate reached 66.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"The state of housing in America is very, very good," Nicolas
Retsinas, director of the Joint Center for Housing Studies, was
quoted by the Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the growth has occurred outside of cities and in the
South and the West, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that increases in immigration and in the number
of young or newly formed households will fuel a continued increase
in the housing market for the next decade. At the same time, baby
boomers becoming senior citizens are expected to help sustain the
home remodeling market as they revamp their homes, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
More members of minority groups are buying homes because of low
interest rates and specially tailored mortgage loan programs, the
study found. Minority households now account for 30 percent of
first-time homebuyers, up from 19 percent in 1985, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
