<HEADLINE> PLO Backs UAE's Position on Gulf Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) said here on Monday that
the Palestinians back the United Arab Emirates (UAE) on its
dispute with Iran over three Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) took a firm position
on the issue, said Mahmoud Abbas, Secretary-General of PLO's
Executive Committee, who is on a visit to the UAE.
</P>
<P>
"We support the UAE's peaceful approaches of solving the issue
through negotiations or referring the dispute to the
International Court of Justice," Abbas was quoted by the official
WAM news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a statement after meeting with UAE Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed al-Nahyan, Abbas said
their talks covered bilateral ties and current issues in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he briefed Sheikh Hamdan on the results of
the May Israeli elections and the efforts being made to form a new
Israeli cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The three islands, Abu Musa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs, located
near strategic shipping lanes in the Gulf, are claimed by both the
UAE and Iran but have been occupied by Iran since 1971, when
Britain withdrew from the region.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has just solved a quarrel with its Gulf ally Saudi
Arabia, who recently improved ties with Iran. The UAE had required
Saudi Arabia and other Gulf allies, such as Qatar, Bahrain, Oman
and Kuwait, to link relations with Iran to the solution of the
islands issue. 
</P>
