<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Pledges to Continue Servicing $8Bln </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania pledged Monday to
continue servicing the eight-billion-U.S. dollar external debts to
sustain its credibility to the donor community, a statement from
the State House said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that President Benjamin Mkapa will remain
committed to paying the external debts to ensure a reliable flow
of foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
"President Mkapa is very much concerned about the debt relief
to ensure that developing countries including Tanzania have a
respite in debt servicing to enable them better provision of
social services," it said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania established the Multilateral Debt Relief Fund (MDF)
last year aimed at lessening the serving of the external debt and
ensuring better provision of social services.
</P>
<P>
Several less developed countries including Uganda, Mozambique,
Guinea Bissau and Bolivia have also started the same fund to
ensure better provision of social services.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Tanzanian Finance Ministry show that a
total of 50.4 billion Tanzanian shillings (one U.S. dollar equals
some 710 Tanzanian shillings) have already been pledged to support
the fund.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that during his meeting with the visiting
Managing Director and Corporation Secretary of the World Bank
Zhang Shengman Saturday, Mkapa said that Tanzania, a
highly-indebted poor country (HIPC), is facing difficulties in
servicing external debts.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa appealed to the World Bank to assist Tanzania to attain
debt relief within a shorter time frame under the HIPC initiative.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's commitment to servicing the external debts
encouraged the donors to cancel a total of 700 billion Tanzanian
shillings in debt in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa asked the World Bank to consider Tanzania's request
following its successful implementation of a three-year economic
reform program put forward by the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Zhang commended Tanzania for its impressive performance in
regard to economic reform program, promising to cooperate with
Tanzania in marketing its agricultural potential.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has actively supported Tanzania's economic
development efforts by financing more than 130 projects since the
1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
