<HEADLINE> Angola,Two Congos to Join Hands for Common Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Interior Minister Fernando
da Piedade Dias dos Santos said Monday that his country will join
hands with two Congos to ensure stability and security along their
common borders.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Angola, Congo (Brazzaville) and Congo (Kinshasa)
have set out to establish a joint police force to ensure stability
and security along their common borders by reinforcing check
points, concerting patrols and coordinating military operations.
</P>
<P>
The interior ministers of the three countries held a meeting in
Kinshasa recently, reaching an agreement on cooperation among
their police forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, priorities are given to preventing
the rebels from launching attacks from the land of the other
country. And the three countries will also take measures to curb
the smuggling of arms, diamonds and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Angola has a 2,000-km common border with Congo (K), the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). For long, the rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has been using
its bases in the DRC. Recently, the UNITA forces established
alliance with the rebels there.
</P>
<P>
Angola shares common border with Congo (B), the Republic of
Congo, in its northern enclave Cabinda Province. The separatists
frequently launch attacks on the petroleum-rich province from the
border.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government of President Denis Sassou-Nguesso
also hopes to win support from the Angolan army in quenching the
rebellion in his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
