<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Parties Satisfied With G-8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Most Greek Cypriot parties Monday
expressed satisfaction with the reference to Cyprus in the G-8
summit statement issued Sunday in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 (seven most industrialized nations plus Russia)
statement urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in accordance
with relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions to invite the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders to negotiations in the fall of
1999.
</P>
<P>
However, the parties also expressed reservations with the
reference included in the G-8 statement that "all issues (will
be) on the table."
</P>
<P>
Ruling right-wing DISI party leader Nicos Anastasiades
expressed satisfaction with the fact that the G-8 countries are
interested in the Cyprus issue and are becoming active.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Cyprus issue remains within the
U.N. framework and a settlement will be based on the Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Main opposition party AKEL parliamentary representative Andreas
Christou said the reference to the U.N. resolutions on Cyprus is
positive.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that other references could allow the Turkish
side to place its unacceptable condition for a confederation in
Cyprus on the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
President of center-right DIKO Spyros Kyprianou said the
statement proves that the G-8 will become involved in efforts for
a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said that even though the reference has some positive
aspects it includes some points which must be clarified.
</P>
<P>
Similar views were expressed by the socialist EDEK leader,
Vasos Lyssarides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
