<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Avoid Clashes Over Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Environment Minister
Bernardo Ferraz Monday urged to avoid clashes over the management,
utilization and development of the natural resources shared by the
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Ferraz made the call at a regional workshop on African natural
resources in Mozambican capital Maputo, the Mozambican News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that there might be regional conflicts
over natural resources unless the African countries coordinate
their steps in the management, use and development of these
resources.
</P>
<P>
He cited water as one of the most important resources which may
possibly cause conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that various countries sharing common waters
should coordinate their policies on the management, use and
development of the resources.
</P>
<P>
The sectors most likely to fall victim to such clashes include
agriculture and energy, Ferraz was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, Ebenizario Chonguica, representative of the
World Conservation Union in Mozambique, also urged the African
countries to protect the natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from South Africa, Kenya, Zambia, Malawi, Namibia,
Botswana, Zimbabwe, Angola and Finland and some non-governmental
organizations attended the seminar to be closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Land and population, forest and wild life and mineral resources
and energy will also be addressed at the workshop. 
</P>
