<HEADLINE> French New Gaullist Party Elects President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- France's new Gaullist party, the
Rally for France (RPF), Monday elected its founder Charles Pasqua
as its president.
</P>
<P>
Charles Pasqua, who was interior minister in the former
conservative government of Edouard Balladur, established the RPF
after the European Parliament election on June 13.
</P>
<P>
The RPF won 13 percent of the votes in the election, the second
biggest win after the Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
Pasqua, who is often called "sovereigntyist" for his opposition
to France's adherence to the European single currency and a wider
European political integrity, caused a mini-earthquake to the
French rightwing by breaking away from the Rally for the Republic
(RPR) of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The new RPF leader also opposed France's participation in the
NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
His close associate, former RPR parliament deputy Philippe de
Villiers, was elected the vice president of RPF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
