<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: Uzbek Mistrust of Turkey Baseless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit Monday dismissed as baseless suspicions raised by
Uzbekistan that Turkey provides support and shelter for Uzbek
anti-government forces.
</P>
<P>
"The suspicions and concerns of Uzbek President Islam Karimov
are unfounded," Ecevit told reporters, adding that Turkey attaches
great importance to its relations with Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
"I can not accept that bilateral relations are harmed because
of such a sensitivity," said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He played down suggestions that the schools opened in
Uzbekistan by Turkish religious leader Fethullah Gulen, who faces
charges of anti-secularism, had fueled the tension between Ankara
and Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think this is the reason...I think there is an
unnecessary mistrust, " Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
Uzbekistan's apparent conviction that Uzbek dissidents have
received support and shelter from Turkey has led to a severe
diplomatic crisis between the two countries, with Ankara recalling
its ambassador to Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
The tension erupted after two Uzbek dissidents, suspected of
participating in a February assassination attempt on Karimov,
surfaced in Istanbul and Ankara did not proceed with their
extradition as quickly as Tashkent demanded.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, the Uzbek authorities have decided to close
down more than 20 Turkish schools in their country and have
ordered the immediate return of 220 Uzbek students studying in
Turkish universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
