<HEADLINE> 6 Iraqi Civilians Injured in U.S., British Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Six Iraqi civilians were injured
Monday in U.S. and British warplanes attacks on civilian
facilities, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 16:20 (1220 GMT), 16 formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated
southern Iraqi airspace over Basra, Misan, Thi-Qar and Muthana
provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy planes attacked some civil service installations,
leaving six civilians injured, said the spokesman, adding that
Iraqi air defenses counter-attacked the enemy planes and forced
them to flee to their bases.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:05 (0705 GMT), eight formations
of enemy planes coming from a Turkish air base violated northern
Iraqi airspace over Neineva, Dohuk and Erbil provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy planes bombed some civilian facilities in this
region, said the spokesman. No casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq
last December, their warplanes have made 1,695 and 7,275 sorties
over the northern and southern no-fly zones respectively, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting
the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
possible attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
