<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Preparatory meetings on the signing
of a cease-fire in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) started
here Monday with rebel delegation expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Zambian Ministry of Foreign Affairs
confirmed that delegates from the countries concerned had started
arriving here for a series of meetings that would culminate into
the heads of state summit on June 26.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the ministers of defense meeting would be
held on June 23 and rebels fighting to oust DRC President Laurent
Kabila are expected to participate in all the meetings.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Zambian government was still waiting for
confirmations from Rwanda, Uganda, Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia, the
DRC and other countries and world bodies before the ministers of
defence meeting could start.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, who is spearheading the
peace initiative, has already invited former South Africa
President Nelson Mandela, former Tanzanian President Julius
Nyerere and former Botswanan President Ketumile Masire to witness
the signing of the peace documents.
</P>
<P>
Invitation had also been extended to Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), Salim Ahmed Salim, the United
Nations and Gabonese President Omar Bongo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Lusaka International Airport shortly before
departure for Blantyre, Malawi, to attend the swearing-in ceremony
of re-elected President Bakili Muluzi Monday morning, Chiluba said
that the latest demands by DRC rebels would be discussed during
negotiations after Saturday' s signing of a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that they (DRC rebels) will try and push things
out of context. It is not the chair that will look in their
demands, but it is what will take place in the negotiating
process," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president is scheduled to host the summit, during
which a cease-fire is expected to be signed by all the
belligerents in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He has been mandated by the Southern African Development
Community (SADC)

to lead the cease-fire initiative aimed at ending the 11-month
conflict in the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
But the rebels have given a set of demands which they say must
be met before they agree to sign the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Among the demands are that DRC President Kabila's forces should
stop bombing civilian targets, release political prisoners and
agree to hold direct talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The rebel delegation led by Emile Ilunga, President of the
Congolese Rally for Democracy is in Lusaka to meet Chiluba and to
take part in preparatory talks ahead of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government officials said that the 10-man rebel team
included former Congolese Foreign Minister Bizima Karaha and other
senior members of the political and military wings of the rebel
movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
