<HEADLINE> Security Council Voices Concern on Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday expressed concern over the situation in Congo (K) and
expressed the hope to see a successful outcome of the peace talks,
scheduled for June 26 in the Zambian capital of Lusanka.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement read to the press, the president of the
Security Council, Ismaila Jane of Gambia, said, "The members of
the Security Council expressed concern over the situation there
and expressed the hope for a successful outcome" of the planned
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council is preparing a statement on this issue
for adoption within a week," he said.
</P>
<P>
The press statement came after the 15-nation Security Council
met in a closed-door session to hear the briefing on the political
situation in the African country by Moustapha Niasse, the U.N.
special envoy for the Democratic Republic of Congo, also known as
Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The briefing coincided with the preparation for the peace
talks, slated for Wednesday in Lusaka, capital of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The rebels took up arms in August last year in a bid to topple
the Congo (K) Government, headed by President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda back the rebels while Kabila has won military
support from Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the mediation by Zambian President Frederick Chiluba,
the parties to the conflict have agreed to send ministers to
Lusaka on Wednesday for talks that would include rebels, and the
warring parties' presidents would meet without rebels on Saturday
to sign a ceasefire accord, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba's concept of peace, if achieved, would require the
costly deployment of United Nations peacekeepers. The plan
involves a ceasefire between Congo, its allies and Rwanda and
Uganda, and a separate one between Kingshasa and the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
