<HEADLINE> Turkey Outlines Conditions for Resuming Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a
statement Monday that the acknowledgment of the existence of
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" is the only way to the
resumption of bilateral talks in the long-divided Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The ministry issued the statement in response to Sunday's call
of the G-8 summit for the resumption of talks in Cyprus with no
preconditions in the upcoming autumn.
</P>
<P>
The seven most industrialized countries plus Russia (G-8)
stressed in their summit held in Cologne, Germany, that the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot communities should be committed "in good faith
to continue to negotiate until a settlement is reached."
</P>
<P>
And leaders of the G-8 hinted that the November summit of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in
Istanbul, Turkey, should be a deadline for a conclusion of the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "instead of forcing the parties to
negotiate under a definite timetable, the reasons for the failure
of previous talks should be carefully examined and an appropriate
atmosphere and basis should be created for productive talks."
</P>
<P>
It added that any negotiation process will be doomed to fail if
the parameters are not determined on the basis of realities on the
island and if the present lack of confidence is not eradicated.
</P>
<P>
"At present, there are two equal sovereign and democratic
states in Cyprus which represent the two peoples there," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that "a solution to the problem can be durable
only if it is outlined not by the third parties but by these two
states and if it maintains the balance between Turkey and Greece."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
