<HEADLINE> Moscow Hails End of War in Yugoslavia, Blasts NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Monday welcomed the end
of war in Yugoslavia but reiterated its condemnation of NATO for
its armed adventure that flouted the generally recognized norms
and principles of international law, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"It has been our consistent position that the Kosovo issue has
no military solution and (we have) called on all sides to look for
a way out of the crisis only by political means through
negotiations," the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"From the start of NATO's aggression against Yugoslavia, our
country strongly condemned it and pressed for an immediate end to
armed violence. The Russian side exerted maximum effort to stop
the air strikes on the territory of Yugoslavia and return the
process of Kosovo settlement to the political footing," Tass
quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the NATO aggression caused catastrophic
consequences. "Yugoslavia has been completely ruined. The damage
caused to its national economy and infrastructure exceeds all
destruction during World War II."
</P>
<P>
"Now top priority tasks are the deployment in Kosovo of an
international civilian presence and a security presence under the
U.N. auspices, the resumption of talks on political settlement
with full respect for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of work is to be done to restore the Yugoslav economy,
including in Kosovo, and other countries in the region," the
statement said. "Russia will actively cooperate in this with all
interested sides." 
</P>
</TEXT>
