<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Extends Contract Probe to 1970s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
Monday ordered to extend a probe of the unfinished projects
tracing back to the year 1976 to cover his own tenure as the Head
of State then.
</P>
<P>
At the inauguration of a 12-member probe panel in Nigerian
capital Abuja, Obasanjo announced the decision in response to
criticism for the probe.
</P>
<P>
He said the extension, to cover his tenure between 1976 and
1979 and that of second republic president Alhaji Shagari from
1979 to 1984, should "help allay fears that this is not a probe."
</P>
<P>
The president said that the original 14-year-mandate from 1984
has been "misconstrued as a probe" of governments after the
military takeover in 1984.
</P>
<P>
"This is far from the objective, which is to provide an
inventory of uncompleted projects, supplies and services," said
Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The panel would investigate hundreds of contracts, including
the abandoned presidential villa in Abuja, which were awarded and
in some cases paid for without completion.
</P>
<P>
It would also determine whether due process was followed in
their award and advise the government.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is time to turn our attention to critical
economic issues affecting our policy including that of such
projects," said Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The panel has nine months to complete its work, three months
shorter than in its original mandate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
