<HEADLINE> Interior Ministers of Western Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of the
Western Mediterranean countries gathered here Monday for a two-day
conference.
</P>
<P>
Interior ministers from Algeria, Spain, France, Libya, Italy,
Morocco, Portugal and Tunisia attended the meeting, the fifth of
its kind.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will discuss combating organized crimes,
narcotics, illegal immigration, and cooperation in the areas of
civil defense and local communities, the Algerian News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Opening the conference, Algerian Minister of Interior, Local
Collectivities and Environment Abdul-Malik Sallal said the meeting
shows the member countries' collective will to continue the
regional cooperation that started several years ago.
</P>
<P>
On Algeria's anti-terrorism campaign over the recent years,
Sallal said efforts are being made to fight terrorism and to curb
its spread.
</P>
<P>
Algeria kept warning the international community against the
dangerous contagion of terrorism, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's continuous efforts to attract the world attention to
the danger of terrorism were not designed to derive mere
denunciation, but to establish bases for regional cooperation that
can help uproot terrorism completely within the framework of law
and international pacts, Sallal noted.
</P>
<P>
The first conference of interior ministers of the Western
Mediterranean countries was held in January, 1995, in Tunis.
</P>
<P>
The second conference was held in Morocco in April, 1996, the
third in France in April, 1996 and the fourth in Italy in May,
1998. 
</P>
