<HEADLINE> Israeli Court Rejects Vanunu's Appeal for Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel's High Court rejected an
appeal for early release of Mordechai Vanunu, who is serving an
18-year sentence for disclosing Israel's nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
Vanunu said in his first appeal that he should be allowed to
return to Italy after 13 years in jail, according to Israel
Channel One. The court rejected the appeal.
</P>
<P>
Vanunu, a former technician at Israel's Dimona nuclear plant,
was abducted from Italy to Israel reportedly by Israeli agents in
1986 after telling Britain's Sunday Times newspaper that Israel
had more than 200 atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
However, the court accepted his second appeal, agreeing to make
public parts of the judgements or protocols in his case, which
have never been released.
</P>
<P>
The documents might be publicized Tuesday after the state
prosecutor and security officials decide Monday night which parts
should be deleted, the television report said.
</P>
<P>
Vanunu, 44, was taken out of solitary confinement last
year. His lawyer said Monday that his mental health has been
improved since then, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In order to keep a vague deterrent force, Israel carries out a
"don't ask, don't tell" policy on its nuclear programs, never
confirming nor denying any reports on these programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
