<HEADLINE> Irish Health Farms Say No to GM Foods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's health farms on Monday
declared themselves opposed to genetically modified (GM)
foodstuffs, saying they would work towards eliminating such foods
from their menus.
</P>
<P>
The Health Farms of Ireland Association said in a statement its
members had become increasingly concerned by recent reports of
health risks associated with GM foods and by the apparent failure
of governments to implement adequate safeguards, according to a
Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason the association has decided to declare itself
opposed to GM foods. It is our stated aim to serve food that is
completely GM-free," it said.
</P>
<P>
Consumer and other groups, including the British Medical
Association, have called for a moratorium on GM crop planting
until scientists agree they are safe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
