<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990622.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed IMF Gold Sale Lamented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Proposals for the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to sell 10 percent of its gold
to assist debt relief among the world's poorest countries "are
flawed", the World Gold Council (WGC) said in a press release here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The recent fall in the price of gold as a direct consequence
of the plans of the IMF, Switzerland and the United Kingdom to
sell gold, has already lost these developing nations more than 150
million U.S. dollars in annual export earnings," the release said.
</P>
<P>
"This is more than they stand to gain from the IMF's proposed
sale of 10 percent of its gold reserves," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The impact of these potential sales has raised concerns
world-wide and led the WGC to commission a study by independent
economists into the effect of such sales on the economies of
gold-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
The 80-page study, entitled "A Glittering Future?", sets out
the role gold plays in the macro-economic life of many of the
world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
The study says that these countries are just beginning to
broaden their export base, away from dependency upon one or two
agricultural commodities and toward industrial growth, assisted by
their embryonic gold mining industries.
</P>
<P>
Gold mining has helped boost not only their export revenues but
also played an important part in strengthening their legal,
financial and economic development.
</P>
<P>
"This process is now threatened by the falling gold price," the
report says.
</P>
<P>
Of the 41 heavily-indebted poor countries, or HIPCs, more than
30 are gold producers or potential producers. In nine of them,
gold accounts for at least five percent of export revenues and in
other two of them for more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Annual gold production in the HIPCs is set to be 200 tons in
the year 2000. In global terms, this may not sound much, slightly
less than 10 percent of annual global production, but for the
countries concerned this is an important contribution to export
and tax revenues," Gary Mead, head of Research at the WGC, told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
At 280 U.S. dollars an ounce, projected export earnings for
these countries from gold would total 1.66 billion dollars by the
end of 2000, according to Mead.
</P>
<P>
"Compared with 10 years ago, there is now a large gap between
supply (mine production) and demand (mostly jewellery)," he said.
"In order to help fill this gap, gold mining would provide solid
and viable export growth for these countries if it were not for
the damaging impact of major threats from official sales."
</P>
<P>
The researcher said the WGC argues that leaders of the G-7
countries should refrain from approving the gold sales for two
essential reasons:
</P>
<P>
-- The IMF's proposed sale of 10 million ounces (311 tons) has
already (in conjunction with other official sector sales)
adversely affected the international price of gold, and thus has
inadvertently damaged the economic development of many of those
countries the HIPC initiative aims to assist;
</P>
<P>
-- The IMF proposes to invest the proceeds (about 2.3 billion
dollars) from the gold sale, and use a proportion of the yield on
that to help fund debt relief. If invested in U.S. government
bonds the interest may amount to some five percent a year, about
110 million dollars. Thus the benefit of the sale (110 million
dollars a year ) has already been more than offset by the economic
cost, a loss of more than 150 million dollars annually as a result
of the fall in the gold price.
</P>
<P>
"Without careful reconsideration of the damage which has
already been done to the fledgling gold mining industry of many of
the world's poorest countries by the threat of gold sales, their
glittering future may be still- born," the WGC press release said.
</P>
<P>
"The World Gold Council calls upon all official gold holders,
including the UK, to consider the consequences for the poorest
gold producing countries when planning any sales," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
