<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Withdraw Some Forces From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Monday it intended
to withdraw some air forces and naval ships from the Serbian
province of Kosovo as the NATO air campaign was over.
</P>
<P>
"RAF (the Royal Air Force of the United Kingdom) air and ground
crews will soon be coming home to their loved ones and so will be
some of the Royal Navy ships which have been on station for so
long in the Adriatic," Defense Secretary George Robertson told a
news briefing.
</P>
<P>
But he did not give any details, stressing that there would
still be NATO aircraft and ships available in that region.
</P>
<P>
"We have not dropped our guard. NATO will still act if it is
provoked," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
During various stages of the Kosovo crisis, Britain had
deployed a total of 13,000 military personnel in the region.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Britain decided to send 60 armed police officers to
Kosovo to "help form a new police force" as part of efforts to
rebuild the shattered province.
</P>
<P>
NATO's devastating bombardment of Serbian targets killed nearly
1,000 civilians and caused the exodus of a large number of
refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
